[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "1. Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ Black develops a piece and prevents White from establishing the d4/e4 pawn centre, while keeping his opponent in the dark about how he is going to move his pawns. }
2. c4 c5
{ This can lead to either the Benoni or the Benko Gambit. These openings are a family of dynamic defenses in chess where Black concedes a space advantage to White in return for fluid long range potential on the dark squares.   It should be noted that Black could first play  2...e6  and only choose to play the pawn to c5 if White commits to 3. Nf3  (thereby cutting out a few critical variations, such as the Taimanov/Four Pawns Attack)  . But I have faith in Black's chances and encourage you to learn the sharpest lines with 2... c5. Enter into the jungle! }
3. d5
{ If White does not want to play against the Benoni  (or the Benko Gambit)   he can choose  3.Nf3  , when play is likely to transpose into a symmetrical English opening.   There are a few non-critical alternatives here, such as  3.dxc5   and  3.e3  that we will look at in the final Odds and Ends chapter. }
3... e6
{ Black intends to take on d5. In the Modern Benoni Black strives to open the e-file to maximize the potential of the rook and queen. }
4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5
{ 5.Nxd5?!  is played very rarely. While White temporarily exploits the d5-square, he breaks several basic rules - do not move the same pieces several times in the opening, and do not exchange pieces when you have a space advantage because it allows your opponent to relieve his cramped position. We will deal with this option in the Odds and Ends chapter. }
5... d6
{ Black secures the c5 pawn and takes control of the important e5-square. As we shall see this breakthrough point plays a crucial role in White's plans. }
6. e4
{ White's main alternative is  6.Nf3  ,  which can still transpose to some 6. e4 lines, but often White has other ideas, such as an early Bf4, or the trendy - thanks to the books of GM Boris Avrukh -  6...g6  7.g3  fianchetto system. }
6... g6
{ This is the main tabiya for this course. The fianchettoed bishop is a stronghold for Black in the plan of active play on the dark squares.   From here White has several options. We will start out by looking at the classical mainline of  7.Nf3  Bg7  8.Be2  ,   And then turn to the modern mainline of  7.Nf3  Bg7  8.h3!?.  Here I offer two answers -  8...O-O  9.Bd3  b5  , which has been analyzed into a slightly worse endgame for Black,   and  9...a6!?  , which does not offer full equality but leads to imbalanced positions in which there are more opportunities to outplay your opponent.   Then we will look at the complex of the Four Pawns Attack,  7.f4  , starting with two chapters on the Taimanov variation  7...Bg7  8.Bb5+  ,   After which there follow two chapters on the more straightforward  7.f4  Bg7  8.e5.   I also offer the alternative  7.f4  Qe7!?  which is less solid than the main lines but has a lot less theory and is a good surprise weapon.   From there we go to the Penrose attack,  7.Bd3  Bg7  8.Nge2  , which is very sharp but can be defused with accurate play,   and then the Saemisch,  7.f3  ,   and its close relation  7.Nge2  Bg7  8.Ng3. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "Bukhuti Gurgenidze vs. Mikhail Tal, Moscow 1957"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. e4 Bg7 8. Be2
O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. Nd2 Na6
{ Our preference is  10...Nbd7  - see chapter 7, line  50.  Tal intends to move the knight to c7 in preparation of ...b7-b5 or otherwise ...b6 and ...Ba6  - swapping off the c8-bishop that is often difficult to deploy for Black in the Modern Benoni. }
11. Re1 Nc7 12. a4 b6 13. Qc2 { This relinquishes control over the g4-square. }
13... Ng4 { Tal immediately pounces on the opportunity to attack. } 14. h3
{ After  14.Bxg4  Bxg4  15.Nc4  there still wouldn't have been anything wrong with White's position. }
14... Nxf2 { A thunderbolt. } 15. Kxf2
{ 15.Nf3  was better, but after  15...Bxc3  16.bxc3  Nxe4  White probably doesn't have enough compensation for the two pawns. }
15... Qh4+ 16. Kf1 Bd4 17. Nd1 Qxh3 { Even stronger than  17...Bxh3. } 18. Bf3
{ Of course, White cannot retake due to  18.gxh3?  Bxh3#  mate. } 18... Qh2
{ Now White has to reckon with the possibility of ...Qg1+. } 19. Ne3 f5
{ Tal opens the e- and f-files as a prelude to the conclusion of his attack. }
20. Ndc4 fxe4 21. Bxe4 Ba6 22. Bf3 Re5
{ The computer spots that the cold-blooded  22...g5!  followed by ...g4 was even stronger. Tal's play is more simple: he doubles rooks while increasing the pressure on the d5-pawn. }
23. Ra3 Rae8 24. Bd2
{ This allows a conclusive blow, although White's position was lost anyway. }
24... Nxd5 25. Bxd5+ Rxd5 { Because  26.Nxd5?  Qg1#  is not possible. } 26. Ke2
Bxe3 27. Rxe3 Bxc4+
{ White resigned due to  28.Qxc4  Qxg2+  29.Kd1  Qxd2#   and  28.Kd1  Rxe3  29.Rxe3  Qg1+  30.Re1  Qf2!  with the deadly threat of ...Bb3. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "Yuri Averbakh vs. Mikhail Tal, Riga 1958"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Be2 Bg7 8. Nf3
O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. Qc2 Na6
{ With White's queen on c2 Black also has the idea of posting his knight aggressively on b4. }
11. Bf4 Nb4 12. Qb1 Nxe4
{ One of those crazy sacrifices that Tal was known for. } 13. Nxe4 Bf5 14. Nfd2
Nxd5 15. Bxd6
{ 15.Bg3  would have posed significantly more problems for Black to solve. A sample line runs  15...Bh6!?   15...Nf6  16.Bd3  Nxe4  17.Nxe4  c4  18.Bc2  Bxe4  19.Bxe4  d5  20.Bf3  and Black doesn't have enough compensation for the piece  16.Bb5  Bxd2  17.Bxe8  Qxe8  18.Nxd6  Bxb1  19.Nxe8  and Black has some compensation for the exchange but White is still better. }
15... Nf6 { Now White's pieces are just overextended. } 16. Bf3 Nxe4 17. Nxe4
Bxe4 18. Bxe4 Qxd6
{ Because  19.Bxb7?  Rab8  is bad for White, Black is just a pawn up for no compensation. }
19. Qc2 Re7 20. Bf3 Rae8 21. Rad1 Bd4
{ Thanks to his extra pawn Black also has this nice outpost for his bishop. In positions with opposite coloured bishops, the person who is first to set up an attack on the opponent's king usually wins. }
22. a4 b6 23. b3 Re5 24. Rd2 h5 25. Re2 Rxe2 26. Bxe2 h4
{ White would like to create a 'luft' for his king, but h2-h3 would severely weaken the dark squares, while g2-g3 currently isn't possible. }
27. Kh1 { 27.g3?  hxg3  28.hxg3  Qxg3+ } 27... Qf4 28. g3 Qf6 29. Qd1 Rd8 30.
Bg4
{ Overlooking some tactics.  30.Qd3  was necessary, when  30...Bxf2?  can be met by  31.Rxf2! }
30... Bxf2 31. Qe2
{ Now  31.Rxf2  doesn't work because  31...Rxd1+  comes with check. Still, hasn't Black trapped his own bishop? }
31... Rd2
{ Averbakh probably missed this move. The rook is immune due to ...Qc6+ and mate. }
32. Qe8+ Kg7 33. gxh4 Qd4 34. Bh3 Qd3 35. Bg2 Rd1
{ After  36.Qb5  Rxf1+  37.Bxf1  Qe4+  38.Bg2  Qxh4  Black is two pawns up for nothing. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "Gert Ligterink vs. John Nunn, Marbella 1982"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. g3 Bg7 8. Bg2
O-O 9. O-O Nbd7
{ In the theory section I recommend  9...Re8  to establish control over the e4-square first. }
10. e4 a6 11. Bf4 Qe7 12. Re1
{ Perhaps  12.e5!?  dxe5  13.d6  was more dangerous. } 12... Ng4
{ Now Black can establish a firm blockade on the e5-square. } 13. Bg5 Qe8 14.
e5 Ndxe5 15. Nxe5
{ Now  15...dxe5?  16.d6  followed by Nd5 would give White very nice play, but Black has something extraordinary in mind. }
15... Nxe5 16. f4 Ng4 { The point - a positional queen sacrifice! } 17. Rxe8
Rxe8
{ Black only has a rook and a pawn for the queen, but the g5-bishop is in trouble, Black controls the only open file and he has ideas of ...Ne3 as well as the direct threat of ...Bd4+. }
18. Ne2 { Preventing ...Bd4+. } 18... Ne3 19. Qd2 Nc4 20. Qc2 b5 21. g4
{ It's hard to find a good move for White, but this can't be it. } 21... Bxg4
22. Ng3 h6 23. Bh4 Bxb2 24. Rc1
{ The rook has almost no squares.   24.Rb1  Bd4+  25.Kh1  Na3   24.Rf1  Bd4+  25.Kh1  Ne3 }
24... Bd4+ 25. Kh1 Ne3 26. Qd2 Nxg2
{ This exchange could have backfired. It was safer to return with  26...Nc4. }
27. Qxg2
{ 27.Kxg2!  and suddenly White has an advantage because of the threat of f5! with an attack.  27...Be3  28.Qc2  Bxc1  29.Qxc1  and White still has the threat of f5,   While  27.Kxg2  Be3  28.Qc2  Bxf4  29.Ne4!  also sets up an attack on the weak dark squares. }
27... Re3 { Now Black keeps the initiative. The threat is ...Bf3. } 28. Rf1
Rae8 29. f5
{ 29.h3  first was necessary. After  29...Bc8  30.f5  , the move  30...g5  can be answered by  31.Nh5. }
29... g5 30. f6 Kh8 { Now White just loses a piece. } 31. Bxg5 hxg5 32. Nf5
Bxf5 33. Rxf5 Re1+ 34. Rf1 Bxf6
{ 34...g4!  followed by 35... R8e2 would have picked up White's queen. } 35.
Qh3+ Kg7 36. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 37. Kg2 c4
{ White has no checks and Black's queenside pawns will decide the game. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Taimanov Mainline"]
[Black "2. Taimanov Mainline: 13. Bc4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4
{ We shall now cover White's most aggressive systems where he launches an early pawn storm. }
7... Bg7 8. Bb5+
{ This disruptive check known as the Taimanov System has long been considered the most challenging for Black. As we shall see though, the early movement of the bishop will force White to concede time  (in the event that it retreats)  or actual weakness on the queenside  (when White plays a2-a4 weakening the b4-square)  . }
8... Nfd7
{ Practice has proved that this is the best way to block the check and maintain control of e5.   The issue with the natural  8...Nbd7 ?!  is that White can advance  9.e5 !  ,  gaining a tempo on the f6-knight, and after  9...dxe5  10.fxe5  Nh5  11.e6  the d7-knight is lost. After  11...Qh4+  hair-rising complications arise, but this line has long been known to favor White. }
9. a4
{ This is the most-played move. With the bishop on b5 Black will be able to play ...a6  (gaining a tempo on the b5-bishop)  and ...b5, establishing a nice pawn front on the queenside. a2-a4 is aimed against this space-grabbing action by Black. }
9... O-O 10. Nf3 Na6
{ The knight heads to b4 where it will be a constant thorn in White's queenside. }
11. O-O Nb4 12. Re1 a6 13. Bc4 Nb6
{ A nice trick to know. Black gains time after which he can develop his bishop to g4. }
14. Bf1 Bg4 15. Be3 Bxf3
{ We play this immediately because White cannot retake with the queen -  16.Qxf3 ?  Nc2. }
16. gxf3 Qh4
{ The queen is strongly positioned here, eyeing up White's pawn weaknesses. Black should continue with ...Nd7 and then either play for the ..f5 pawn break, or try to prepare ...b5 and ...c4. }
*

