[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4
{ We shall now cover White's most aggressive systems where he launches an early pawn storm. }
7... Bg7 8. Bb5+
{ This disruptive check known as the Taimanov System has long been considered the most challenging for Black. As we shall see though, the early movement of the bishop will force White to concede time  (in the event that it retreats)  or actual weakness on the queenside  (when White plays a2-a4 weakening the b4-square)  . }
8... Nfd7
{ Practice has proved that this is the best way to block the check and maintain control of e5.   The issue with the natural  8...Nbd7?!  is that White can advance  9.e5!  ,  gaining a tempo on the f6-knight, and after  9...dxe5  10.fxe5  Nh5  11.e6  the d7-knight is lost. After  11...Qh4+  hair-rising complications arise, but this line has long been known to favor White. }
9. a4
{ This is the most-played move. With the bishop on b5 Black will be able to play ...a6  (gaining a tempo on the b5-bishop)  and ...b5, establishing a nice pawn front on the queenside. a2-a4 is aimed against this space-grabbing action by Black. }
9... O-O 10. Nf3 Na6
{ The knight heads to b4 where it will be a constant thorn in White's queenside. }
11. O-O Nb4 12. Re1 a6 13. Bc4 Nb6
{ A nice trick to know. Black gains time after which he can develop his bishop to g4. }
14. Be2 Bg4
{ But don't I lose the two bishops? Yes, but you gain much more control of the e5 and d4 squares plus White's remaining light-squared bishop is a 'bad bishop' that is blocked by the pawns. }
15. h3 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 Qh4
{ Black probes for weakness followed by Nc4 looking for more. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Taimanov Mainline"]
[Black "4. Taimanov Mainline: 13. Bf1, 14. Be3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4
{ We shall now cover White's most aggressive systems where he launches an early pawn storm. }
7... Bg7 8. Bb5+
{ This disruptive check known as the Taimanov System has long been considered the most challenging for Black. As we shall see though, the early movement of the bishop will force White to concede time  (in the event that it retreats)  or actual weakness on the queenside  (when White plays a2-a4 weakening the b4-square)  . }
8... Nfd7
{ Practice has proved that this is the best way to block the check and maintain control of e5.   The issue with the natural  8...Nbd7?!  is that White can advance  9.e5!  ,  gaining a tempo on the f6-knight, and after  9...dxe5  10.fxe5  Nh5  11.e6  the d7-knight is lost. After  11...Qh4+  hair-rising complications arise, but this line has long been known to favor White. }
9. a4
{ This is the most-played move. With the bishop on b5 Black will be able to play ...a6  (gaining a tempo on the b5-bishop)  and ...b5, establishing a nice pawn front on the queenside. a2-a4 is aimed against this space-grabbing action by Black. }
9... O-O 10. Nf3 Na6
{ The knight heads to b4 where it will be a constant thorn in White's queenside. }
11. O-O Nb4 12. Re1 a6 13. Bf1 Re8
{ Before playing ...Nf6 we make our presence known on the e-file. } 14. Be3
{ White plans to cross over to the kingside via f2 and h4. Black should respect this plan and take care to stop it ! }
14... Nf6 { freeing the c8-bishop and reminding White about the e4 square. }
15. Bf2 Bg4
{ Black now sets his sight on the c2 square; Black would like to take on f3 and force White to make a choice between mutilating his pawn structure or allowing a fork on c2. }
16. Rc1 Nd7
{ Now that the light-squared bishop has been developed, the knight goes back again to this square ! Black has stopped Bh4 and can proceed with queenside play with ...Rc8. Also in some cases Black can strike the center with ...f7-f5. }
17. h3 Bxf3 18. Qxf3 Rc8 19. b3 Bd4
{ A paradoxical move; often times in the conquest of the dark squares Black exchanges bishops and then invades on the absent dark squares with the remaining pieces and pawns. }
20. Red1 Qf6
{ Keeping the tension. We would like White to exchange on d4 instead of us exchanging on f2. }
21. Bc4 g5
{ Going all out for the occupation of the e5-square and the g-file ! } *

