1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4
{ We shall now cover White's most aggressive systems where he launches an early pawn storm. }
7... Bg7 8. e5
{ White goes straight for the throat but runs a huge risk of being overextended. }
8... Nfd7 9. e6
{ This only looks scary. White cannot hope to launch an attack without having developed his pieces. }
9... fxe6 10. dxe6 Nb6
{ This is superior to  10...Nf6  because in the latter case White can keep the e6-pawn with  11.Bc4. }
11. Ne4 { Now White is in serious difficulties. } 11... O-O
{ Development is key here. The e6-pawn won't run away. } 12. Qxd6 Qxd6
{ Even after the trade of queens Black will have a strong initiative. } 13.
Nxd6 Bxe6 14. Nxb7 c4
{ Black is down a pawn but is actually close to winning. He is far ahead in development and has strong pressure against White's queenside - ...c4-c3 ! being a direct threat. In addition, White's king is unsafe and the b7-knight is in danger of being trapped. }
*

