7... Bg7 8. e5
{ White goes straight for the throat but runs a huge risk of being overextended. }
8... Nfd7 9. Nb5
{ This is more testing than  9.e6.   Note that  9.Ne4  dxe5  10.Nd6+  leads to the same position. }
9... dxe5
{ The only move. Black should not allow White's knight on d6 to be supported by a f4-e5 pawn chain with   9...O-O ?  10.Nxd6. }
10. Nd6+ Ke7 { Black should immediately challenge the d6-knight. } 11. fxe5
{ This is much worse than  11.Nxc8+. } 11... Nxe5 12. Nxc8+ Qxc8 13. d6+ Kf8
14. Nf3 Qe6
{ Black achieves an outcome similar to what happens after 11. Nxc8+, but with better development. }
15. Nxe5 Bxe5
{ Because Black is still threatening a discovered check, he buys enough time to move his king comfortably to g7. }
16. Be2 Kg7 17. O-O Nc6
{ Black is already up a pawn and the d6-pawn will soon be won as well. } *

