[White "4. Four Pawns Attack"]
[Black "21. Four Pawns Attack: 9. Nb5, 11. Nxc8+"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4
{ We shall now cover White's most aggressive systems where he launches an early pawn storm. }
7... Bg7 8. e5
{ White goes straight for the throat but runs a huge risk of being overextended. }
8... Nfd7 9. Nb5 { This is more testing than  9.e6. } 9... dxe5
{ The only move. Black should not allow White's knight on d6 to be supported by a f4-e5 pawn chain with   9...O-O?  10.Nxd6. }
10. Nd6+ Ke7 { Black should immediately challenge the d6-knight. } 11. Nxc8+
Qxc8 12. Nf3 e4
{ The mainline here is  12...Re8  ,  but the counter sacrifice ...e5-e4 is of at least equal value. Plus there is far less to learn and the move has surprise value. Furthermore this was the choice of the great Benoni specialist GM Vugar Gashimov. }
13. Ne5
{ This natural move is new. White offers more material to open the f-file and the c1-bishop's diagonal so that it can be developed with check. }
13... Nxe5 14. fxe5 Bxe5 15. d6+ Bxd6 16. Bg5+ Kd7
{ Three pawns to the good, Blacks king runs to the shelter of the queenside. }
