[White "5. Four Pawns Attack Mainline"]
[Black "28. Four Pawns Attack Mainline: 10. Nd2, 12. a4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4
{ We shall now cover White's most aggressive systems where he launches an early pawn storm. }
7... Bg7 8. Nf3
{ A standard developing move, White's most played after  8.Bb5+. } 8... O-O
{ A simple rule when developing: start with the moves that you are going to play regardless, so that you keep your options open for the pieces that you aren't sure where you are going to place them yet.In this case, Black wants to castle and put his rook on e8 anyway, but he keeps White in the dark on where he is going to develop his b8-knight  (to d7 or to a6 and then b4 or c7)  and the c8-bishop  (to g4 or to b7 or even a6)  . Additionally, White is behind in development so it makes sense to immediately pressure the e-file on which his king still resides. }
9. Be2 Re8 { The e4-pawn is hanging. } 10. Nd2
{ This is a more positional approach for White where ideally he would like to play O-O, ♗f3 and then ♘c4 followed by breaking through with e4-e5. Black has a number of ways to prevent this plan. }
10... Na6
{ Since we know White is aiming to breakthrough with e4-e5 it is sensible to build pressure against the d5-pawn, as the e4-e5 advance will leave this d-pawn without support. }
11. O-O Nc7 12. a4
{ White wants to be sure that Black won't be able to play ...b5 anytime soon. }
12... b6 13. Re1 Ba6 14. Bf3
{ This doesn't work out well for White, but after  14.Bxa6  Nxa6  Black has no problems either - he can put his knight on b4 from where it exerts pressure on the d5-pawn, and then prepare to play ...a6 and ...b5. }
14... Bd3 { This bishop is really annoying for White. } 15. Nf1 c4
{ This gave Black excellent play in Shankland, S.  2602  vs. Gao, R.  2454  , Santa Clara 2014. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Four Pawns Attack Mainline"]
[Black "29. Four Pawns Attack Mainline: 10. e5, 12. e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4
{ We shall now cover White's most aggressive systems where he launches an early pawn storm. }
7... Bg7 8. Nf3
{ A standard developing move, White's most played after  8.Bb5+. } 8... O-O
{ A simple rule when developing: start with the moves that you are going to play regardless, so that you keep your options open for the pieces that you aren't sure where you are going to place them yet.In this case, Black wants to castle and put his rook on e8 anyway, but he keeps White in the dark on where he is going to develop his b8-knight  (to d7 or to a6 and then b4 or c7)  and the c8-bishop  (to g4 or to b7 or even a6)  . Additionally, White is behind in development so it makes sense to immediately pressure the e-file on which his king still resides. }
9. Be2 Re8 { The e4-pawn is hanging. } 10. e5
{ We reach the traditional mainline of the Four Pawns Attack. This same position can also be reached with a King's Indian move order. White is placing all his hopes on the shock and awe tactics of the central pawn phalanx, but with deft movement Black can cut through White's offensive and neutralize the attack. }
10... dxe5 11. fxe5 Ng4
{ Now the path divides: White can choose between 12. e6, 12. Bg5 and 12. O-O. }
12. e6 fxe6 13. d6
{ White hopes to get compensation in the form of his passed pawn on d6 and Black's weakened pawn structure and king's position. }
13... Rf8
{ Black simply puts the rook on the best square and challenges White's entire concept. }
14. Bg5 Qb6
{ Putting pressure on b2 and making it hard for White to castle kingside. } 15.
Qd2
{ After  15.O-O?  Qxb2  Black wins material - he is threatening ...Bxc3, but if the knight moves, say  16.Ne4  , then  16...Qxa1  picks up the exchange. }
15... Nc6
{ Simply developing.   Note that  16.d7 ?  is nothing to fear, since after  16...Bxd7  17.Qxd7  Qxb2  both the a1-rook and c3-knight are hanging. }
16. O-O Nd4 { I do not see anything for Black to fear here. } *

