7... Bg7 8. Nf3
{ A standard developing move, White's most played after  8.Bb5+. } 8... O-O
{ A simple rule when developing: start with the moves that you are going to play regardless, so that you keep your options open for the pieces that you aren't sure where you are going to place them yet.In this case, Black wants to castle and put his rook on e8 anyway, but he keeps White in the dark on where he is going to develop his b8-knight  (to d7 or to a6 and then b4 or c7)  and the c8-bishop  (to g4 or to b7 or even a6)  . Additionally, White is behind in development so it makes sense to immediately pressure the e-file on which his king still resides. }
9. Be2 Re8 { The e4-pawn is hanging. } 10. e5
{ We reach the traditional mainline of the Four Pawns Attack. This same position can also be reached with a King's Indian move order. White is placing all his hopes on the shock and awe tactics of the central pawn phalanx, but with deft movement Black can cut through White's offensive and neutralize the attack. }
10... dxe5 11. fxe5 Ng4
{ Now the path divides: White can choose between 12. e6, 12. Bg5 and 12. O-O. }
12. Bg5
{ Time to buckle up! We are going down a long forced line that leads to an endgame with better chances for Black. }
12... Qb6 { Now both the b2- and e2-pawns are hanging. } 13. O-O Nxe5
{ The other pawn is poisoned for the moment:  13...Qxb2?  14.Nb5!  and White is threatening both Rb1 and Nc7. }
14. d6 Qxb2 { White has to do something about his hanging knight. } 15. Nd5
Nxf3+ 16. Bxf3 Bd4+
{ It is useful to first push White's king away from the center. We will soon enter an endgame, and in endgames it is important to have a centralized king instead of one on the edge of the board. }
17. Kh1 Qxa1 18. Qxa1 Bxa1 19. Rxa1
{ Black is two pawns and the exchange up for the moment, but White is threatening both Nc7 and Nf6+ and has a dangerous passed d-pawn. }
19... Re5
{ Here there is some debate about  19...Nd7  , but I think it is nice to have the option to return the exchange sacrifice. }
20. Bf4 Rxd5 21. Bxd5 Nc6
{ Black should simply finish his developments at the cost of a pawn and he will have no problems. }
22. Bxc6 bxc6 23. Rc1 Bd7 24. Rxc5 f6 { Black is fine here. } *

