20. Ne7+ Kg7 21. Nxc8 Nd7
{ A very important detail: both  21...Rxg5 ?  22.Bxb7   and  21...Nc6 ?  22.d7  win for White.  We are entering into a rook versus B+N ending where Black's mobile rooks and passed c-pawn secure him an advantage. }
22. Bxb7 Rb8 23. Bc6 Rxg5 24. Bxd7 c4
{ It is crucial to tie down White's forces to this pawn. } 25. Nxa7 c3 26. Ba4
Rc5
{ A very strong move. The immediate  26...Rd5  allows  27.d7  , when White's passed pawn is a source of counterplay. }
27. Bc2 { 27.h3  c2  28.Bxc2  Rxc2  should win for Black. } 27... Rd5
{ Now White does not have the d6-d7 resource while the c3-pawn remains a thorn in White's side and the a7-knight is still likely to be trapped. }
28. h3
{ A necessary move.  28.a4  Rb2 !  29.Be4  c2  -+ and White has to give up his bishop. }
28... Rxd6
{ Now  28...Rb2  29.Rc1  is less clear, e.g.  29...Rd2  30.Bb3  Rxg2  31.Rxc3. }
29. Rc1 Rb7
{ White has prevented the c3-pawn from causing too much trouble, but now the poor knight is about to meet its end. }
30. Nc8 Rd8 { Picking up the trapped knight. } *

