[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. 7...Qe7 Alternative to Four Pawns/Taimanov"]
[Black "38. 7...Qe7 Alternative: 8. Bd3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4
{ We shall now cover White's most aggressive systems where he launches an early pawn storm. }
7... Qe7
{ This is an interesting alternative to the main lines of the Four Pawns Attack and the Taimanov variation. Black reinforces the e5 breaking point and delays playing Bg7 which can lead to some independent ideas. I feel this line is somewhat risky if White has perfect understanding, but that is just the point; ...Qe7 is a good surprise weapon ! }
8. Bd3
{ White informs us that he will not be playing Bb5, so now it is safe to play ...Bg7 followed by O-O. }
8... Bg7 9. Nf3 O-O 10. O-O c4
{ A nice nuance that attempts to punish White's commitment to an early Bd3. }
11. Bxc4 { This allows Black to gain an advantage in the center. } 11... Nxe4
12. Re1 { Another dubious move. } 12... Nxc3 13. bxc3 Qc7
{ Not only is the c3-pawn ripe for the picking, Black has a nice outpost for his knight on c5 and has a nice choice of where to develop his c8-bishop, which is unusual in the Benoni! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. 7...Qe7 Alternative to Four Pawns/Taimanov"]
[Black "39. 7...Qe7 Alternative: 8. Bd3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4
{ We shall now cover White's most aggressive systems where he launches an early pawn storm. }
7... Qe7
{ This is an interesting alternative to the main lines of the Four Pawns Attack and the Taimanov variation. Black reinforces the e5 breaking point and delays playing ♗g7 which can lead to some independent ideas. I feel this line is somewhat risky if White has perfect understanding, but that is just the point; ...♕e7 is a good surprise weapon! }
8. Bd3
{ White informs us that he will not be playing ♗b5, so now it is safe to play ...♗g7 followed by ...O-O. }
8... Bg7 9. Nf3 O-O 10. O-O c4
{ A nice nuance that attempts to punish White's commitment to an early ♗d3. }
11. Bc2 Bg4
{ Black's strategy is to minimize White's control over the e5-square. } 12. h3
Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Na6
{ Black can look forward to playing ...Nb4, again causing White's light-squared bishop some trouble. }
14. Be3
{ 14.a3  Nc5  15.Bd2   15.Be3  Ncxe4!  16.Nxe4  Nxe4  17.Bxe4  Rae8  15...a6  and Black can follow up with ...b5 when he has an initiative on the queenside while he has contained White's kingside advances. }
14... Nb4 15. Bb1 Rfe8
{ Increasing Black's pressure on e4 and control over e5. } 16. Re1 b5
{ If White takes this pawn, e4 will be hanging. } 17. a3 Nd3 18. Bxd3 cxd3
{ This pawn transformation can be seen in a number of Benoni lines. The idea is that the d3-pawn will act as a nuisance for White to actually capture and maintain piece harmony. Also, the exchange of our knight for White's light-squared bishop has weakened the e4-pawn. }
19. Bd2 Nd7
{ The knight will be strongly positioned on c5 or, alternatively, c4. } 20.
Qxd3 Nc5 21. Qc2 a5 22. Nxb5 Nxe4 23. Bc3 f5
{ Even with an extra pawn White has real trouble fully consolidating the position due to his overextended pawns on d5 and f4. The secret is that Black has exchanged off just enough pieces to minimize the chance of kingside or central attack. }
