{ Making space for the c1-bishop to move to g5. This is a new move that has not been found over the board by pro level chess players. Do you think your opponent will find it? }
13... Bxf3 { This try also doesn't seem to work. } 14. Bxd7
{ Of course, White doesn't allow us to establish an uncontested knight on e5. }
14... Rxd7 15. e6
{ Another strong in-between move. This also looks very good for White to me. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. 7...Qe7 Alternative to Four Pawns/Taimanov"]
[Black "46. 7...Qe7 Alternative: 8. Nf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4
{ We shall now cover White's most aggressive systems where he launches an early pawn storm. }
7... Qe7
{ This is an interesting alternative to the main lines of the Four Pawns Attack and the Taimanov variation. Black reinforces the e5 breaking point and delays playing ♗g7 which can lead to some independent ideas. I feel this line is somewhat risky if White has perfect understanding, but that is just the point; ...♕e7 is a good surprise weapon! }
8. Nf3
{ White dares us to capture the e4-pawn which would lead to a nasty double attack with ♕a4+. }
8... Bg4 9. Bb5+ { One of the most critical tests of the 7... ♕e7 line. } 9...
Nbd7 10. O-O O-O-O
{ Castling long in the Benoni is the path for chess adventures for sure !   10...Bg7?  would be far too slow. After  11.e5  White wins a piece. }
11. Qa4
{ White has not won a single game in this position in my database but I do have some bad news... if you are playing against a computer, at least. }
11... Kb8 12. e5 { Our fears become reality ! } 12... Ne8 13. f5
{ Making space for the c1-bishop to move to g5. This is a new move that has not been found over the board by pro level chess players. Do you think your opponent will find it? }
13... Bxf3 { This try also doesn't seem to work. } 14. Bxd7
{ Of course, White doesn't allow us to establish an uncontested knight on e5. }
14... Qxd7 15. Qxd7 Rxd7 16. e6 { Again this strong in-between move. } 16...
Rc7 17. Rxf3 gxf5 18. Nb5
{ This is the critical computer like point. Now White does have a winning attack. With that said I will again encourage Black players to experiment with 7... Qe7!? as an interesting sideline that will most likely confuse their ill-prepared opponents. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. 7...Qe7 Alternative to Four Pawns/Taimanov"]
[Black "47. 7...Qe7 Alternative: 8. Nf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4
{ We shall now cover White's most aggressive systems where he launches an early pawn storm. }
7... Qe7
{ 7... Qe7 is an interesting alternative to the four pawns attack and Taimanov mainlines. Black reinforces the e5 breaking point and delays playing Bg7 which can lead to some independent ideas. I feel this line is somewhat risky if White has perfect understanding, but that is just the point; Qe7 is still a good surprise weapon ! }
8. Nf3
{ White dares us to capture the e4-pawn which would lead to a nasty double attack with ♕a4+. }
8... Bg4 9. Bd3 { This is less critical than 9. Bb5+. } 9... Nbd7
{ Increasing our control over e5. } 10. O-O Bg7 11. h3 Bxf3
{ This exchange is well-known to be useful in the Benoni to contest the control over the e5-square. }
12. Qxf3 O-O 13. Bd2 a6 14. a4 Ne8 15. Rae1 Nc7
{ We reach a typical Benoni position where it seems that White's position has reached an optimal dynamic state and now runs the risk of over-extending and falling into the entropic heat death of optimism. Remlinger, L.  2420  vs. Adelman, C.  2275  , Chicago 1996 was drawn in 26 moves from this position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Classical Mainline"]
[Black "48. Classical Mainline: 10. Qc2, 11. a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Be2
{ This is the starting position of the classical mainline. White wants to play O-O, Nd2-c4, restrain the queenside and eventually play f2-f4, getting a better version of the positional Four Pawns Attack. }
8... O-O { As usual we start with castling and putting a rook on e8. } 9. O-O
Re8 { e4 is hanging. } 10. Qc2 Na6
{ With the queen on c2 White has to be worried about Black playing ...Nb4. }
11. a3
{ I will now ask the reader to forgive me as I show a typical sequence, where we can see how Black should play when White does a bit of waffling around with no clear attacking plan  (a common scenario)  . }
11... Nc7 { Already looking to play ...b5. } 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bf4 b5
{ This pawn move is possible because if White takes on b5, he gives up the defense of the e4-pawn.   13...Qe7  is a bit too slow, because after  14.Nd2  White has defended the e4-pawn and has also prevented the ...b7-b5 advance. }
14. Rfe1 a6 { Shoring up the queenside. } 15. Nd2 Bg4
{ The exchange of light-squared bishops is in Black's favor here, while if White plays f2-f3 we can retreat the bishop and then try to probe the dark squares with ...Nh5. }
16. Bf1 g5 17. Bg3 Bh5
{ Followed by ...Bg6 and ...Nh5. One thing that is certain in this complex position is that White will not be able to break through with e4-e5 or put a knight on c4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Classical Mainline"]
[Black "49. Classical Mainline: 10. Qc2, 11. a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Be2
{ This is the starting position of the classical mainline. White wants to O-O, play ♘d2-c4, restrain the queenside and eventually play f2-f4, getting a better version of the positional Four Pawns Attack. }
8... O-O { As usual we start with castling and putting a rook on e8. } 9. O-O
Re8 { e4 is hanging. } 10. Qc2 Na6
{ With the queen on c2 White has to be worried about Black playing ...♘b4. }
11. a3
{ I will now ask the reader to forgive me as I show a typical sequence, where we can see how Black should play when White does a bit of waffling around with no clear attacking plan  (a common scenario)  . }
11... Nc7 { Already looking to play ...b5. } 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bh4 b5 14. b4
{ In case of  14.Bxf6  Bxf6  15.Nxb5  Black will get a lot of compensation for the pawn in the form of control over the dark squares and pressure on b2, for example:  15...Rb8  16.Nc3  Bg4  17.h3  Bxf3  18.Bxf3  Nb5  19.Nxb5  Rxb5  20.Rab1  Qb6  21.b3  Rb8  and White has to take up a very passive position with  22.Bd1  in order not to give back the pawn immediately. }
14... g5 15. Bg3 c4
{ This type of locked structure is very important to study, as it can turn out badly if White is given the time to break through at the b5-point with a2-a4 or with e4-e5. As usual Black should seek to optimize his pieces and look for dynamic exchanges. }
16. Rad1 Nxe4
{ Boom. Here it is. A key idea always in the Modern Benoni is how best to exploit the weakness at e4. }
17. Nxe4 Bf5 18. Nfd2 Nxd5 19. Bf3 Nc3 20. Qxc3 Bxc3 21. Nxc3
{ Crazy stuff, right ? Perhaps your computer can out run mine, but I can promise you that if you learn this theme of the ...Nxe4 sacrifice your opponents will not know what hit them.   Objectively White may be a bit better in this position, but it is difficult for White to coordinate his pieces accordingly. Black's objective should be to exchange as much pieces as possible and limit the activity of White's dark-squared bishop, which is currently a bit boxed in on g3. A sample line is   21...Bd3 !  22.Bxa8  Qxa8  23.Rfe1   23.Bxd6 ?  Rd8  leaves White in trouble on the d-file;   23.Nxb5 ?!  Qc6  24.Nc3  f5 !  gives Black the initiative.  23...Rxe1+  24.Rxe1  Qb8  - guarding both b5 and d6 -  25.h4  f5 !  with a very complicated position. }
*

