1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Be2
{ This is the starting position of the classical mainline. White wants to O-O, play ♘d2-c4, restrain the queenside and eventually play f2-f4, getting a better version of the positional Four Pawns Attack. }
8... O-O { As usual we start with castling and putting a rook on e8. } 9. O-O
Re8 { e4 is hanging. } 10. Nd2 Nbd7
{ Since there is nowhere for our c8-bishop to go at the moment, we start by developing the b8-knight to a natural square. }
11. f4
{ White returns to the Four Pawns Attack themes, but this allows Black a nice counter shot. }
11... c4
{ This is a nice trick to know. The point is that White won't be able to take the c4-pawn without giving up the e4-pawn. }
12. Bxc4 { Let's see what happens if White takes the pawn. } 12... Nc5
{ e4 is hanging. } 13. Qf3 Bg4 { Developing with gain of tempo. } 14. Qg3 Ncxe4
{ Regaining the pawn. This leads to a series of exchanges that end up in Black's favor. }
15. Ncxe4 Nxe4 16. Nxe4
{ 16.Qxg4 ?  Qb6+  17.Kh1  Nf2+  18.Rxf2  Qxf2  and Black has a winning attack. }
16... Rxe4 17. Bd3
{ In case of  17.Qxg4  Black can flick in ...f5 or ...Qb6+ before taking the c4-bishop, keeping a clearly superior position. }
17... Qb6+ 18. Kh1 Be2 { Powerful play by Black. } 19. Bxe4 Bxf1 20. Be3 Qb4
{ Depending on what White does with the e4-bishop Black can continue with ...Bc4, ...Ba6 or ...Re8. Black is better because his pieces are more active and have an easier time targeting White's pawn weaknesses. }
