{ This is a solid move, but it reduces White's control over the g4-square and makes him prone to tricks involving ...Nxe4 and ...Bf5  (the b1-h7 diagonal)  . }
11... Ne5
{ Putting our knight on this nice central square, we dare White to chase it away with f2-f4. }
12. a4
{ White holds up the ...b7-b5 advance, preparing to put a knight on c4. } 12...
g5
{ This was the innovation of Bobby Fischer in 1970. Black restrains the f2-f4 push and is even planning to grab more space with ...g4 followed by ...Nh5. It is also interesting to explore   12...Bg4  which we analyze against 12. b3  (very similar in spirit)  . }
13. Nc4 Nxc4 14. Bxc4 Nh5 { Black has good play on the dark squares. } 15. Ne2
Qe7 16. f3 Be5 17. Bb5 Rf8 18. g4 Nf4 19. Nxf4 gxf4
{ And Black was ready to advance the h-pawn in Hesselbarth, K. vs. Horatschek, M., DDR 1988. }
