15. f4 Ng4 { Sending in the probes. } 16. Nd1
{ If White allows ...Bd4+ he can resign. } 16... Bxb2 17. Qxb2 Nxh2
{ In the style of Tal ! } 18. Kxh2 Qh4+ 19. Kg1 Ng3
{ Against most responses Black can force a draw with ...Qh1+ followed by ...Qh4, but he can also play for more if he wants to. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Classical Mainline"]
[Black "60. Classical Mainline: 10. Nd2, 11. Qc2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Be2
{ This is the starting position of the classical mainline. White wants to O-O, play ♘d2-c4, restrain the queenside and eventually play f2-f4, getting a better version of the positional Four Pawns Attack. }
8... O-O { As usual we start with castling and putting a rook on e8. } 9. O-O
Re8 { e4 is hanging. } 10. Nd2 Nbd7
{ Since there is nowhere for our c8-bishop to go at the moment, we start by developing the b8-knight to a natural square. }
11. Qc2
{ This is a solid move, but it reduces White's control over the g4-square and makes him prone to tricks involving ...Nxe4 and ...Bf5  (the b1-h7 diagonal)  . }
11... Ne5
{ Putting our knight on this nice central square, we dare White to chase it away with f2-f4. }
12. b3 Bg4
{ An interesting idea by Fabiano Caruana. Black intends to provoke a weakness on the kingside. }
13. Bxg4 Nfxg4
{ The other knight should remain on e5 from where it oversees White's entire position. }
14. Bb2 a6 15. h3 Nf6 16. f4 Ned7
{ Black is being pushed back, but this is only temporarily. } 17. Nc4
{ It looks like White has got everything he was dreaming about. Let's see how the world number 2 handles this with ease. }
17... Nb6 { Exchanging White's powerful c4-knight is a must. } 18. Rae1
{ 18.Nd2  would allow  18...c4 !  followed by ...Rc8. } 18... Nxc4 19. bxc4 Nd7
{ Dodging the coming e4-e5 break and maximizing Black's control over e5. Black would like to follow up with ...b7-b5 here. }
20. e5 { White decides to play e5 anyway. } 20... dxe5 21. f5
{ A very important and typical pawn sacrifice for White that we will see time after time. In this particular case it seems that White lacks the assault force to really press for checkmate. }
21... b5 { Key idea: returning the pawn for piece play ! } 22. Ne4 Nb6
{ This was debated at the highest level by Aronian and Caruana at the Candidates tournament in 2016. Black is doing very well, keeping White busy on the queenside and in the center. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Classical Mainline"]
[Black "61. Classical Mainline: 10. Nd2, 11. a4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Be2
{ This is the starting position of the classical mainline. White wants to O-O, play ♘d2-c4, restrain the queenside and eventually play f2-f4, getting a better version of the positional Four Pawns Attack. }
8... O-O { As usual we start with castling and putting a rook on e8. } 9. O-O
Re8 { e4 is hanging. } 10. Nd2 Nbd7 11. a4
{ White can maintain the queen at d1 and play a sort of waiting game with Re1, h2-h3 and Nf1 to follow. Here Black can enjoy easy play with ...a6/...Rb8/...Ne5 and keep an eye on the h5 square for an eventual ...Nh5. }
11... a6 12. Re1 Rb8 13. Ra3
{ A creative rook lift that has had success against the Benoni. } 13... Ne5 14.
a5
{ Against this move I have prepared something very special! Now before we go any further I also want to let you know it is still perfectly fine to continue with the plan of  14...g5  followed by ...Ng6 and so on. This may be more to taste thematically with less to learn, but I just cannot resist showing a few novelties against White's formation with a rook on a3 and a queen on d1. }
14... Nh5
{ I find it amazing that no one has attempted this 'Fischer-esque' move here. For those unaware, in the game Spassky - Fischer  (World Championship 3rd round, Reykjavik 1972)  the American surprised everyone with the similar move ...Nh5!?, allowing White to inflict doubled h-pawns on him. But doing so gave Black increased control over the g4-square, an open g-file to work with and in general strong play on the kingside.In any case, in this position White cannot win a pawn by taking twice on h5. }
15. Bxh5
{ What else  ?  15.Nf1  would be met with the probe  15...Qh4  and good play. }
15... gxh5 16. h3
{ The pawn grab  16.Qxh5 ?  fails to  16...Bg4  , trapping the queen. } 16...
h4
{ Black has a nice dark square grip plus the two bishops. I dare say this idea of ...Nh5 will once again become more and more popular. }
*

