[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. h3
{ With this move White prepares to play Bd3, O-O and Bf4; a formation that has become the modern mainline.  White starts with h3 because the immediate   8.Bd3 ?!  allows  8...Bg4 !  followed by an eventual taking on f3 and Nbd7-e5 with easy equality for Black. }
8... O-O 9. Bd3 b5
{ This pawn advance ruins White's plans of a steady build up. The only downside is that there is a line with a forced draw in the endgame, but this is a reality of modern chess. In the next chapter I will provide an alternative if you must play for a win, but 9... b5 is the most correct path. }
10. O-O
{ This allows Black to take the initiative.   10.a3?!  does not stop the advance  10...b4  either, and is considered in model game #6. }
10... b4 11. Ne2 Re8 { Developing with gain of tempo. } 12. Ng3 Ba6
{ Exchanging a defender of the e4-pawn. } 13. Bxa6 Nxa6 14. Qd3 Qc8
{ Threatening ...c4. } 15. Qc4 Nd7
{ Black will follow up with ...Nb6 and further advances on the queenside. } *

