[White "8. Modern Mainline"]
[Black "65. Modern Mainline: 10. Nxb5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. h3
{ With this move White prepares to play Bd3, O-O and Bf4; a formation that has become the modern mainline.  White starts with h3 because the immediate   8.Bd3 ?!  allows  8...Bg4 !  followed by an eventual taking on f3 and Nbd7-e5 with easy equality for Black. }
8... O-O 9. Bd3 b5
{ This pawn advance ruins White's plans of a steady build up. The only downside is that there is a line with a forced draw in the endgame, but this is a reality of modern chess. In the next chapter I will provide an alternative if you must play for a win, but 9... b5 is the most correct path. }
10. Nxb5 { This is the best bet for White to play for an advantage. } 10... Re8
{ Black will regain the pawn. } 11. Nd2 { This is obscure but challenging. }
11... Nxd5 12. Nc4 Re6 13. Be2 Nb6 14. Ncxd6
{ This allows White to win a pawn temporarily, but he is behind in development and his knights are a mess. }
14... Ba6 { Putting maximum pressure on White's knights. } 15. Bg4 f5 16. Be2
Nc6 { Simply developing is Black's best try here. } 17. Be3 Nd4
{ Black makes good use of the pressure on White's two knights. } 18. Bxd4 Bxd4
19. Qb3
{ It looked like Black was getting the better of it but this pin is very annoying. }
19... c4
{ The only move. This leads to a series of exchanges that culminate in an opposite-coloured bishop endgame. }
20. Nxc4 Bxb5
{ Black makes use of the fact that his e6-rook is temporarily unpinned to exchange on b5 and take the e4-pawn. }
21. Qxb5 Rxe4 22. Nxb6 Qxb6
{ Black could keep more material on the board with  22...Rb8  , but after  23.O-O  Rxb6  24.Qc4+  Black's king is less safe than White's. }
23. O-O Qxb5 24. Bxb5 Rb8 25. Bd3 Re7 26. Rab1 Rxb2
{ The smoke has finally cleared. We have entered an endgame that in all likelihood will end in a draw. }
