{ This pawn advance ruins White's plans of a steady build up. The only downside is that there is a line with a forced draw in the endgame, but this is a reality of modern chess. In the next chapter I will provide an alternative if you must play for a win, but 9... b5 is the most correct path. }
10. Bxb5
{ This way of capturing on b5 is less dangerous, but Black does need to know what he is doing. }
10... Nxe4 { A typical tactic. } 11. Nxe4 Qa5+ { Regaining the piece. } 12.
Nfd2 Qxb5 13. Nxd6 Qa6
{ White has won a pawn but Black has excellent piece play and the two bishops. }
14. N2c4
{ 14.Nxc8??  is not possible because of  14...Re8+  with a deadly attack. }
14... Nd7 15. O-O Nb6
{ Breaking the bind of the two knights. The alternative is  15...Ne5  which is also a very good line for Black, but we feel that 15... Nb6 remains viable, is easy to learn and the resulting endgame is drawn. }
16. Nxb6 Qxb6 17. Nxc8 Raxc8 18. Rb1 Rfd8 19. Bf4
{ The most precise. White will keep the extra pawn but won't win the game  (if we play well in the endgame)  . }
19... Qb7 20. d6 Bf8
{ Black can chase down the d-pawn but White is able to switch tracks and gain the a-pawn. }
21. Qd3 Bxd6 22. Bxd6 Rc6 23. Rfd1
{ Now an important choice for Black. He can either give the a-pawn or two rooks for a queen. }
23... Rcxd6 24. Qxd6 Rxd6 25. Rxd6 c4
{ Black can exchange off his weak c-pawn. } 26. Rd2
{ A sample game after  26.Rdd1  went  26...h5  27.Re1  Qb5  28.Rec1  Qf5  29.Ra1  Qd3  30.Rc3  Qe2  31.Rb1  a5  32.a4  Kg7  33.Rbc1  Qxb2  34.Rxc4  h4  35.Rf1  g5  36.Rg4  f6  and Shalimov - Simantsev, Kharkov 2000 ended in a draw after 100 moves. }
26... c3 27. Rc2 Qe4 28. Rbc1 cxb2 29. Rxb2 h5
{ We reach an ending where White has a theoretical advantage, but in practice it is no easy matter to convert the advantage and avoid a perpetual check or worse. Black's queen should keep an eye on White's a-pawn as well as White's king, trying to force concessions whenever White leaves the 1st rank with both his rooks. }
