[White "9. Modern Mainline: Alternate Plan"]
[Black "74. Modern Mainline Alternate Plan: 9... a6, 12. Re1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. h3
{ With this move White prepares to play Bd3, O-O and Bf4; a formation that has become the modern mainline. }
7... Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bd3 a6
{ As an alternative to the drawish and forcing lines of 9... b5!? I will submit to you the plan of ...a6, ...Nbd7 and some creative use of ...Nh5. I will be forthright however in saying that these lines do not offer Black 100% equality but are instead a calculated risk to imbalance the game. }
10. a4 Nbd7 11. O-O Re8 { Here  11...Nh5  is also possible. } 12. Re1 Nh5
{ Now Black can struggle over the f4-square and provoke g2-g4. } 13. a5 b5
{ This leaves Black with a weak a-pawn, but the half-open b-file usually compensates fully for that. }
14. axb6 Qxb6 15. Ra2 Ne5
{ Making space for the c8-bishop and intending to exchange the f3-knight. } 16.
Be2 Nxf3+ 17. Bxf3 Nf6 { White was threatening Bxh5. } 18. Bf4 Bb7
{ White is intending to play e4-e5, so we carry out our standard counter of putting as much pressure as possible on the d5-pawn. }
19. e5 dxe5 20. Bxe5 Rad8
{ This looked fine for Black in Ginsburg, M.  2367  vs. Sevillano, E.  2461  , Los Angeles 2011. }
