1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. h3
{ With this move White prepares to play ♗d3, O-O and ♗f4; a formation that has become the modern mainline. }
7... Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bd3 a6
{ As an alternative to the drawish and forcing lines of 9... b5!? I will submit to you the plan of ...a6, ...♘bd7 and some creative use of ...♘h5. I will be forthright however in saying that these lines do not offer Black 100% equality but are instead a calculated risk to imbalance the game. }
10. a4 Nbd7 11. O-O Re8 { Here  11...Nh5  is also possible. } 12. Re1 Nh5
{ Now Black can struggle over the f4-square and provoke g2-g4. } 13. g4 Nhf6
{ Mission accomplished: though g2-g4 is not always bad for White in the Benoni, here it has significantly weakened his king's position. }
14. Bf4 h5
{ It is important to strike at the kingside pawns before White can consolidate. }
15. g5 Nh7 16. h4 Ne5 17. Nxe5 dxe5
{ Again we learn that this blocked structure is not so bad for Black. ...f7-f6 is coming with real counterplay on the kingside. }
18. Be3 f6 *

