10. a4 Nbd7 11. O-O Re8 { Here  11...Nh5  is also possible. } 12. Re1 Nh5
{ Now Black can struggle over the f4-square and provoke g2-g4. } 13. Bg5
{ This is the most common reaction. } 13... Bf6
{ Black wouldn't mind the exchange of dark-squared bishops as that would increase his control over the f4-square. }
14. Be3 Ne5 15. Be2 Nxf3+ { Again carrying out this standard exchange. } 16.
Bxf3 Ng7 17. Qd2 Bd7
{ Black can also play  17...b6  , which is seen in model game #7. } 18. Bf4
{ In my experience this is how White usually plays for some advantage. Now Black can hold with  18...Be5   or perhaps the experimental exchange sacrifice  18...Re5. }
