{ With this move White prepares to play ♗d3, O-O and ♗f4; a formation that has become the modern mainline. }
7... Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bd3 a6
{ As an alternative to the drawish and forcing lines of 9... b5!? I will submit to you the plan of ...a6, ...♘bd7 and some creative use of ...♘h5. I will be forthright however in saying that these lines do not offer Black 100% equality but are instead a calculated risk to imbalance the game. }
10. a4 Nbd7 11. O-O Re8 { Here  11...Nh5  is also possible. } 12. Bf4 Nh5
{ Now we can play this move with gain of tempo. } 13. Bxd6
{ It is considered risky for White to grab this pawn. } 13... Qb6 14. e5
{ 14.Bh2 ?!  Qxb2  and Black wins at least the exchange. } 14... Bxe5
{ 14...Nxe5 ?  15.Bxe5  Bxe5  16.Re1 !  and the pin on the e-file is very problematic for Black. }
15. Bxe5 { 15.Nxe5  Nxe5  16.Bxe5  likely transposes. } 15... Nxe5 16. a5
{ This move has scored some wins for White, but I think Black should be ok with proper play on the kingside. }
16... Qf6 17. Nxe5 Rxe5 18. Re1 Rxe1+ 19. Qxe1 Nf4
{ Despite the initial reports of engines Black actually has enough kingside pressure to balance the game. I look at this position further in the training position section. }
