1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. h3
{ With this move White prepares to play ♗d3, O-O and ♗f4; a formation that has become the modern mainline. }
7... Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bd3 a6
{ As an alternative to the drawish and forcing lines of 9... b5!? I will submit to you the plan of ...a6, ...♘bd7 and some creative use of ...♘h5. I will be forthright however in saying that these lines do not offer Black 100% equality but are instead a calculated risk to imbalance the game. }
10. a4 Nbd7 11. O-O Re8 { Here  11...Nh5  is also possible. } 12. Bf4 Nh5
{ Now we can play this move with gain of tempo. } 13. Bh2
{ This is a better try than 13. Bxd6. } 13... Ne5
{ Now I will present two different approaches for White: 14. Be2 and 14. Nxe5. }
14. Be2 { The patient approach may be best here. } 14... Nxf3+ 15. Bxf3 Nf6 16.
Qd2 b6
{ Shoring up the a5- and c5-squares in preparation of ...Nd7.   Compare  16...Nd7 ?!  17.Bxd6  Ne5  18.Bxe5  Bxe5  19.a5!  Qf6  to the text - here Black does not have enough compensation for the pawn as White can make use of the queenside with 20. Na4 or even 20. Bd1 followed by Ba4. }
17. Rfe1 Nd7 { This pawn sac is stronger now than on the previous move. } 18.
Bxd6 Ne5 { White has won a pawn but has to give up his dark-squared bishop. }
19. Bxe5 Bxe5 20. Be2 Qf6
{ This would offer Black some compensation in return for a pawn. Practical trials are needed of this somewhat risky plan where Black can look forward to advancing with the g-pawn while holding the center at bay. }
