7... Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bd3 a6
{ As an alternative to the drawish and forcing lines of 9... b5!? I will submit to you the plan of ...a6, ...♘bd7 and some creative use of ...♘h5. I will be forthright however in saying that these lines do not offer Black 100% equality but are instead a calculated risk to imbalance the game. }
10. a4 Nbd7 11. O-O Re8 { Here  11...Nh5  is also possible. } 12. Bf4 Nh5
{ Now we can play this move with gain of tempo. } 13. Bh2
{ This is a better try than 13. ♗xd6. } 13... Ne5
{ Now I will present two different approaches for White: 14. ♗e2 and 14. ♘xe5. }
14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Bxe5 dxe5
{ Now we take control over the f4-square.  15...Rxe5  16.f4  would be going completely against our plans. }
16. Re1
{ Black plays in an unorthodox manner creating a dark-squared blockade. Computers do not think Black has a playable position, but just look at the potential for a kingside expansion in a practical game. }
16... b6
{ Shoring up the queenside in preparation for a kingside attack - now White no longer has counterplay against the c5-pawn or with a4-a5. }
17. b3 Qg5 18. Re3 Nf4 19. Rg3 Qf6
{ Black can follow up with ...h5-h4 and ...g6-g5 etc. } *

