11. Ng3 Nbd7 12. f4 Qc7
{ Black must seek his counterplay on the queenside and down the e-file. } 13.
h3 Rb8 { Intending ...c4 followed by ...b7-b5. } 14. Be3 c4
{ Now we get our standard queenside counterplay. } 15. Bc2 Nc5 16. Bd4 b5 17.
axb5 axb5 18. f5
{ This is a slightly different plan than e5 followed by f5. Here I suggest a new system: }
18... Qe7
{ Providing necessary support to the f6-knight and at the same time putting pressure on the e4-pawn.   18...b4 ?  would normally be good however there is a forcing line Black should avoid:  19.Bxf6  Bxf6  20.fxg6  gives White a strong attack. }
19. Qf3 Ncd7
{ Followed by ...b4 and ...Ne5. It is not clear how White can break through on the kingside. }
