{ Our standard development scheme if White does not prop up the e4-pawn with f2-f3. }
11. Ng3 Nbd7 12. f4 Qc7
{ Black must seek his counterplay on the queenside and down the e-file. } 13.
Bc4
{ This is a sneaky idea. White wants to lure Black's knight to b6 where it will be somewhat misplaced. }
13... Nb6 14. Be2 Nbd7
{ Yes Black lost a move, but is it really so great for White since he can't move his queen to f3? }
15. e5 { White attempts a typical breakthrough. } 15... dxe5 16. f5 e4
{ This is the standard response to the Penrose sealer sweeper sacrifice - push the pawn with ...e4  (giving it back if necessary)  in order to gain the e5-square and open the g7-bishop's diagonal as well as the e8-rook's file. }
17. d6 Qc6 18. Bb5
{ It looks like Black has fallen into a trap but we can channel the spirit of Tal. }
18... axb5 19. axb5 Rxa1 { Welcome to the jungle ! } 20. bxc6 bxc6
{ Stockfish 9 gives the edge to Black in this rather imbalanced position. } *

