{ This is the Penrose Attack, one of White's most ambitious attack formations. It was named after the British Player Jonathan Penrose who crushed the World Champion Mikhail Tal with it at the 1960 Olympiad in Leipzig. White intends to  (later)  develop the knight to g3 from where it supports the f4-f5 advance.   Note that  8.h3  followed by Nf3 would lead to the modern mainline, chapter 8. }
8... O-O 9. O-O a6 10. a4 Re8
{ Our standard development scheme if White does not prop up the e4-pawn with f2-f3. }
11. Ng3 Nbd7 12. f4 Qc7
{ Black must seek his counterplay on the queenside and down the e-file. } 13.
Qf3 c4 { Black relies on the faithful space grab to liberate his army. } 14.
Bc2 Nc5 15. h3 Rb8
{ An improvement over Tal who played in a slower fashion with  15...Nfd7.  Black is ready to roll with pawn to b5. }
16. e5 { The most aggressive reply. } 16... dxe5 17. fxe5 Rxe5
{ This exchange sacrifice is the definite defensive try for Black against the Penrose attack. So far in practical games  (and computer analysis)  the central pressure combined with queenside play has been holding up just fine. }
18. Bf4 Ncd7
{ A novelty. Here Black forces White to react to the threat of Qc5+. } 19. Nge4
Nxe4 20. Nxe4 b5 { Getting our queenside pawns rolling and } 21. Bxe5 Nxe5
{ Not  21...Qxe5??  22.Qxf7+. } 22. Nf6+ Kh8
{ Here we should not trade off our dark-squared bishop unless necessary, since White no longer has his own dark-squared bishop to oppose him with. }
23. Qf4
{ White attempts to keep Black's pieces tied up, but Black can now free himself with a tactical flourish. }
23... Bf5 24. Bxf5 Qb6+ 25. Kh1 Qxf6
{ Black's queenside play and strong piece placement give full compensation for the exchange. }
