[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Bd3 Bg7 8. Nge2
{ This is the Penrose Attack, one of White's most ambitious attack formations. It was named after the British Player Jonathan Penrose who crushed the World Champion Mikhail Tal with it at the 1960 Olympiad in Leipzig. White intends to  (later)  develop the knight to g3 from where it supports the f4-f5 advance.   Note that  8.h3  followed by Nf3 would lead to the modern mainline, chapter 8. }
8... O-O 9. O-O a6 10. a4 Re8
{ Our standard development scheme if White does not prop up the e4-pawn with f2-f3. }
11. Ng3 Nbd7 12. f4 Qc7
{ Black must seek his counterplay on the queenside and down the e-file. } 13.
Qf3 c4 { Black relies on the faithful space grab to liberate his army. } 14.
Bc2 Nc5 15. h3 Rb8
{ An improvement over Tal who played in a slower fashion with  15...Nfd7.  Black is ready to roll with pawn to b5. }
16. Be3 { This is too slow. } 16... b5 17. axb5 axb5 18. e5
{ This is it, the classic Penrose pawn sacrifice. } 18... dxe5 19. fxe5 Rxe5
{ This idea has put the entire Penrose Attack into question. Black can make a strong exchange sacrifice in return for a pawn and good play on the dark squares. }
20. Bd4 { This looks more flexible than 20. Bf4. White skewers e5 and f6. }
20... Rg5 { An annoying counterattack. } 21. Nge2 Nd3
{ 21...Nh5  also looks good here. } 22. Bxd3
{ One of the points of Black's last move is that  22.Bxf6  can be answered by  22...Rf5!  -+ }
22... cxd3 23. Qxd3 Bf5
{ White has regained his pawn but in return Black has the two bishops in an open position and excellent piece activity. }
24. Qd2 h6
{ Black is solid with the two bishops to fend off any attempts at assaulting his king. Black is already threatening ...Bxh3 as well as ...b4 followed by ...Nxd5 and he can attempt to activate his queen via the light squares, e.g. c4. }
