[White "11. Bg5 systems"]
[Black "92. Bg5 systems: 6. Nf3, 7. Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6
{ White can also try to do without an early e2-e4. In any case we stick to our guns with ...g6. }
7. Bg5 Bg7 8. e3 h6 { Pushing the g5-bishop to a more vulnerable square. } 9.
Bh4 g5
{ Since White has taken a more quiet approach  (compared to e2-e4 systems)  we can move forward with more aggression than usual. }
10. Bg3 Nh5
{ In the system with a pawn on e4, I warn against this. But now there is less to worry about since White is farther away from the e4-e5 break. }
11. Bb5+ Kf8
{ We cannot interpose a piece on d7 because of Bxd6+, but this king move is no problem for Black. White will soon lose his dark-squared bishop, after which he will find it difficult to play f2-f4 and e4-e5, which is one of the few ways he can cause trouble for our king on f8. }
12. Bd3 Nxg3
{ We have reached a pet line of the Soviet player V. Antoshin who must have felt that White had a better game  (considering he reached this position at least three times in tournament play in the late 70's)  . I encourage you to delve deeper into model game #8 to see how he was outplayed from here. }
*

