[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Bg5 systems"]
[Black "93. Bg5 systems: 6. e4, 7. Be2, 8. Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Be2
{ An interesting but  (from the Benoni move order)  rare idea. } 7... Bg7 8.
Bg5 O-O
{ Here  8...h6  makes less sense because with the g1-knight as of yet undeveloped, White can just drop back with  9.Be3. }
9. Qd2 a6 10. a4 Nbd7
{ Black is waiting to see how White will continue. If White commits to a Saemisch setup with f2-f3 we would like our rook to remain on f8 to support an eventual ...f7-f5 break. }
11. Nf3
{ 11.f3  is normal and would likely transpose to the Saemisch chapter, variations 138-141. Now, with the knight on f3, White finds it difficult to support the e4-pawn. }
11... Re8 { White probably has to lose time guarding the e4-pawn. } 12. O-O h6
{ Putting the question to the g5-bishop. } 13. Bxh6
{ 13.Bxf6  Qxf6  ∓ is a free bishop pair and dark square domination.   13.Bh4  g5  followed by ...Nxe4 is an extra pawn. }
13... Nxe4
{ Some pieces will be exchanged and White will be left with a weak d5-pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Bg5 systems"]
[Black "94. Bg5 systems: 6. e4, 8. Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Bg5
{ This move is often not mentioned in books and articles, but Black needs to understand how he should respond. White usually only plays Bg5 in conjunction with f2-f3  (the Saemisch)  , as there he does not need to worry about either his e4-pawn or his g5-bishop being vulnerable - the latter can always retreat with Bh4-f2. }
8... h6 { Pushing the bishop to a more vulnerable square. } 9. Bh4
{ Now we always have the option to flick in ...g5 if we want to. } 9... a6
{ An important detail. If Black instead plays  9...g5  10.Bg3  Nh5  he will come under a heavy attack with  11.Bb5+  when the king is forced to step to f8. In comparison with the e3 line we looked at earlier, here White is ready to break through with e4-e5. Therefore we should first prevent Bb5+ and incidentally threaten ...b7-b5 ourselves. }
10. a4 g5
{ I made the choice to have two lines here, 10... g5 and 10... Bg4, as the play is very thematic and instructive. Both moves intend to make it more difficult for White to play the e4-e5 breakthrough. }
11. Bg3 Nh5
{ In the Benoni it is always desirable to exchange White's dark-squared bishop. In this specific instance it also reduces White's control over the e5-square, which means it will be very difficult for him to play the e4-e5 breakthrough. }
12. Nd2 Nxg3 13. hxg3 Nd7 14. Be2 Ne5
{ The knight is perfectly positioned here. } 15. g4
{ 15.f4 ?!  Ng6  and White has no good way to maintain the f4-pawn. } 15... O-O
16. Nf1
{ White has a rather nasty plan of invading on our light squares, but there is one problem. }
16... Qb6 { A strong geometric motif arises against b2 and g4. } 17. Rb1 Nxg4
{ Boom! White is unable to keep his position together. } *

