[Black "95. Bg5 systems: 6. e4, 8. Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Bg5
{ This move is often not mentioned in books and articles, but Black needs to understand how he should respond. }
8... h6 { Pushing the bishop to a more vulnerable square. } 9. Bh4
{ Now we always have the option to flick in ...g5 if we want to. } 9... a6
{ An important detail. If Black instead plays  9...g5  10.Bg3  Nh5  he will come under a heavy attack with  11.Bb5+  when the king is forced to step to f8. In comparison with the e3 line we looked at earlier, here White is ready to break through with e4-e5. Therefore we should first prevent Bb5+ -and incidentally threaten ...b7-b5 ourselves. }
10. a4 g5
{ I made the choice to have two lines here, 10... g5 and 10... Bg4, as the play is very thematic and instructive. }
11. Bg3 Nh5 12. Nd2 Nxg3 13. hxg3 Nd7 14. Be2 Ne5
{ The knight is perfectly positioned here. } 15. g4
{ 15.f4 ?!  Ng6  and White has no good way to maintain the f4-pawn. } 15... O-O
16. Nf1
{ White has a rather nasty plan of invading on our light squares, but there is one problem. }
16... Qb6 { A strong geometric motif arises against b2 and g4. } 17. Ra2 Nxg4
{ Even here ! } 18. Bxg4 Bxg4 19. Qxg4 Bxc3+ 20. bxc3 Qb1+
{ Black regains his sacrificed material with interest. } 21. Qd1 Qxa2 22. Rxh6
Rfe8
{ 22...Kg7  23.Rh7+ !  Kxh7  24.Qh5+  and White escapes with perpetual check. }
23. Ng3
{ White is an exchange down but the position is not so simple, as White's knight is useful in both attack and defense. }
23... Qc4
{ 23...b5  would again allow  24.Rh8+  Kxh8  25.Qh5+  Kg8  26.Qxg5+  , when Black's king can't escape:  26...Kf8  27.Qh6+  Ke7??  28.Nf5+  Kd7  29.Qxd6+  Kc8  30.Qc6+  etc. }
24. Qf3 Qxa4 { 24...Qxd5  is an interesting alternative. } 25. Qf6
{ 25.Rh5  Re5 ! } 25... Rxe4+ 26. Nxe4 Qxe4+
{ Black in any case has perpetual check, but he can force White's king onto c1 or d2 and then try to win the rook endgame:   27.Kd1  Qa4+  28.Kd2  Qf4+!?  29.Qxf4  gxf4  30.Rxd6  Stockfish evaluates the endgame as equal, but Black is the only one who can play for a win with his extra pawn and passed a-pawn. }
