8... h6 { Pushing the bishop to a more vulnerable square. } 9. Bh4
{ Now we always have the option to flick in ...g5 if we want to. } 9... a6
{ An important detail. If Black instead plays  9...g5  10.Bg3  Nh5  he will come under a heavy attack with  11.Bb5+  when the king is forced to step to f8. In comparison with the e3 line we looked at earlier, here White is ready to break through with e4-e5. Therefore we should first prevent Bb5+ -and incidentally threaten ...b7-b5 ourselves. }
10. a4 Bg4
{ The trade of bishop for knight on f3 is a classic exchange for Black. Now we do not have to worry about Nd2-c4 and in general White has a hard time breaking through with e4-e5. As for the two bishops, well perhaps we can eventually force the exchange of the dark-squared bishops or at least neutralize it with a blockade of the e5-point. }
11. Be2 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 O-O 13. O-O Re8 14. Qc2 Nbd7
{ A standard position. Black will keep an eye on e5 while continuing with Rc8 and pushing the pawn to c4. }
