1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Nd2 Bg7 8. Nc4
{ The so called Knight's Tour variation. White plans a quick Nc4 and Bf4, putting pressure on the d6-pawn. Here we have a special counter in mind... }
8... O-O 9. Bf4 Nh5 { Let's give White what he asked for! } 10. Qd2
{ This cannot be critical. } 10... Nxf4 11. Qxf4 Nd7
{ Simply intending ...Ne5 when Black has countered all threats, is ahead in development and has the bishop pair. }
12. Qxd6 Bxc3+
{ 12...b5  is possibly stronger but leads to a lot of complications. The text is a simpler route to an advantage. }
13. bxc3 b5 { Forcing the knight backwards. } 14. Nd2 Qa5 15. Qg3 Re8
{ Followed by ...Nf6 and ...Bb7 with a promising gambit. It is not clear how White will develop since 16. e3? allows 16... Qxc3,   While after  16.e4?!  Nf6  it is impossible for him to defend the e4-pawn. }
*

