[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Nd2
{ The so called Knight's Tour variation. White plans a quick Nc4 and Bf4, putting pressure on the d6-pawn. Here we have a special counter in mind... }
7... Bg7 8. Nc4 O-O 9. Bf4 Nh5 { Let's give White what he asked for! } 10. Bxd6
{ The critical continuation. } 10... Re8 11. Bxc5 Qc7
{ This skewer will force White into some serious contortions. } 12. Qa4
{ The only move. } 12... b5
{ Three pawn sacrifices in a row, but I promise White is the one that is in trouble ! }
13. Qxb5 { 13.Nxb5?  Qxc5  -+ } 13... Bd7
{ The immediate 12... Bd7 allowed 13. Bd6!, but here   14.Bd6  is answered by  14...Bxb5  15.Bxc7  Bxc4  and Black has won a piece. }
14. d6 Qc8 { Keeping the pressure on the pieces on the c-file. } 15. Qa5 Na6
{ ∓ Black will win a piece for the three pawns and White's king is a soft target. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Bf4 systems (no pawn on e4)"]
[Black "109. Bf4 systems: 7. Bf4 and 8. Qa4+"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4
{ This simple developing move is more popular than 7. Nd2. } 7... Bg7 8. Qa4+
{ The point of White's developing scheme: Black faces a choice of giving up castling rights or interposing a piece on d7, which means the d6-pawn would be en prise. }
8... Bd7 9. Qb3 { Now both the b7- and d6-pawns are hanging. } 9... b5
{ This sharp gambit has all but replaced the older  9...Qc7.  Now both players have to walk a narrow path to maintain equality. }
10. Nxb5 { The main try is  10.Bxd6. } 10... Bxb5 11. Qxb5+ Nbd7 12. Bxd6
{ This is more or less forced as apart from ...Nxd5 Black was also threatening ...Rb8! }
12... Ne4 { The d6-bishop has to be removed. } 13. Be5 O-O 14. Bxg7 Kxg7
{ White has won two pawns but is seriously lagging in development. Also, the d5-pawn is weak and he faces issues defending the dark squares on the queenside. }
15. Qa4 Rb8
{ A very strong piece sac, highlighting the dark square weaknesses. Black just keeps going with development sacrificing material. }
16. Qxe4 Qa5+ 17. Nd2 Rxb2 { Threatening mate. } 18. Rd1 Nf6 19. Qd3 Rc8
{ Black has the simple but powerful plan to advance his c-pawn or even attempt to bring both rooks to the second rank.   20.Qc4!?  Rcb8!  21.e4   21.e3  Rxa2  22.Be2  Rbb2  ∓  R8b4  22.Qc3  Rxd2!  23.Qxd2  Nxe4  24.a3!  ∞ is a possible continuation. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Bf4 systems (no pawn on e4)"]
[Black "110. Bf4 systems: 7. Bf4 and 8. Qa4+"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4
{ This simple developing move is more popular than 7. Nd2. } 7... Bg7 8. Qa4+
{ The point of White's developing scheme: Black faces a choice of giving up castling rights or interposing a piece on d7, which means the d6-pawn would be en prise. }
8... Bd7 9. Qb3 { Now both the b7- and d6-pawns are hanging. } 9... b5
{ This sharp gambit has all but replaced the older  9...Qc7.  Now both players have to walk a narrow path to maintain equality. }
10. Bxd6 Qb6 11. Be5 O-O
{ Black has sacrificed a pawn. In return his typical Benoni pawn storm on the queenside is well underway and he also has a lead in development. }
12. e3 b4
{ I prefer this to the more common  12...c4  as it is useful to maintain control of the d4 square. }
13. Nb1 { Intending Nbd2-c4. } 13... Bf5
{ Black is eager to complete development while White is still 2-3 moves away from connecting the rooks. According to most classical theory this is the correct ratio of development to time to play in gambit style. }
14. Nbd2 Nbd7 15. Nc4
{ This is the jam in our gears, Black is forced to undevelop. } 15... Qd8 16.
Rd1 a5
{ This is a sensible novelty. After all, in the Benoni queenside expansion is Black's birthright. I look in detail at two logical moves for White. }
17. a4 Nxe5 18. Ncxe5
{ 18.Nfxe5  allows  18...Nxd5!  when Black can unpin the knight with ...Be6 followed by moving the queen. }
18... Ne4 { Black would like to exchange on e5 and play ...Qh4. } 19. Nc4 Nd6
{ Trading off the anchor of White's position. } 20. Be2 Nxc4 21. Bxc4 Qf6 22.
Rd2 Be4 23. Qd1
{ If  23.Be2  Rfc8!?  with the idea of  24.O-O  Bxf3  25.gxf3  - otherwise ...c4 follows -  Bf8  followed by ...Bd6 with some attacking chances over the dark squares. }
23... b3 24. Bxb3 Rab8
{ This looks very much in the spirit of the Benoni/Benko gambit. } *

