[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nge2
{ This is a cousin of the Saemisch. It leads to positions that are similar to the ones after  7.f3  , but Black should know the exact counter. }
7... Bg7 8. Ng3 a6 9. a4 h5
{ Now Black gains the option of kicking away the g3-knight with a timely ...h4. }
10. Be2 Qe7
{ This is an interesting attempt to force White into playing f2-f3 to protect the e4-pawn. }
11. O-O h4
{ White ignored the threat to e4, so we should take him up on the challenge. }
12. Nh1 Nxe4 13. Re1 O-O
{ Black is just in time with castling to prevent a small problem on the e-file. }
14. Bf1 f5 { The immediate  14...Nxc3  is also fine. } 15. f3 Nxc3 16. bxc3 Qd8
{ Black's kingside pawn structure is a bit loose, but White is not in a position to make use of that. As long as Black keeps an eye on his h4-pawn he should be fine. He can continue to develop with ...Nd7-e5 and perhaps toss in ...f5-f4 to secure the e5-square. }
*

