1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f3
{ The Saemisch proper. } 7... Bg7 8. Nge2
{ An alternative to the main line  8.Bg5.  Now we can play similarly to the previous Nge2 lines. }
8... a6 9. a4 Nbd7
{ Again we delay castling because we might want to use our rook on the h-file. }
10. Ng3 Nh5
{ A fascinating development championed by the Russian top contenders Svidler and Grischuk. Black stakes out space on the kingside and makes the case that the pawn on f3 does not help White attack the weakness at h5. }
11. Nxh5 gxh5 12. Bd3 O-O 13. O-O f5 14. exf5 Ne5 15. Bc2 Bxf5
{ Black had very active play in this rare line. Aronian, L.  2801  vs. Svidler, P.  2763  , Palma de Mallorca 2017. }
