[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f3
{ The Saemisch proper. } 7... Bg7 8. Bg5
{ Most common. White develops his dark-squared bishop aggressively, trying to lure Black into playing ...h6 creating a weakness on the kingside. }
8... O-O { We will simply develop and get on with Benoni business as usual. }
9. Qd2 a6 10. a4 Nbd7 11. Nge2 h6
{ This is possible because White is still weak along the e1-h4 diagonal. } 12.
Bxh6
{ This is never played here but I dare say it is not all that bad for White. }
12... Nxe4 { This is the tactical justificaton of ...h6. } 13. Nxe4 Qh4+ 14. g3
Qxh6 15. Qxh6 Bxh6 16. Nxd6
{ I suspect this is the move that White usually overlooks when considering whether to play 12. Bxh6 or not. }
16... Ne5 { Despite the pawn count Black is doing great in terms of activity. }
*

