9. Qd2 a6 10. a4 Nbd7 11. Nh3
{ This is a natural reaction by White since it is seemingly more fluid to play Nf2 and Be2 rather than Ne2-g3 and Be2. }
11... Qa5 { Black breaks the pin on the f6-knight and threatens ...b7-b5. } 12.
Ra3
{ A standard response - now the rook is protected so that ...b7-b5 is prevented, and the rook might be useful elsewhere on the 3rd rank. }
12... Ne5 { Threatening ...Bxh3. } 13. Nf2 Nh5
{ Once again we find this move being played by strong GMs in the past few years. Let's explore the trend in our games and strive for active play against the Saemisch stronghold. }
14. Be2 f6
{ Before playing ...f5 Black first wants to push the g5-bishop to a less active square. }
15. Be3 f5 16. exf5 gxf5
{ White still can not castle:  17.O-O?  f4  wins a piece. } 17. f4
{ This doesn't solve White's problems. } 17... Ng4 18. Nxg4 fxg4 19. O-O Bf5
{ Black has excellent piece placement. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13. Saemisch"]
[Black "141. Saemisch: 7. f3 and 8. Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f3
{ The Saemisch proper. } 7... Bg7 8. Bg5
{ Most common. White develops his dark-squared bishop aggressively, trying to lure Black into playing ...h6 creating a weakness on the kingside. }
8... O-O { We will simply develop and get on with Benoni business as usual. }
9. Qd2 a6 10. a4 Nbd7 11. Nh3
{ This is a natural reaction by White since it is seemingly more fluid to play Nf2 and Be2 rather than Ne2-g3 and Be2. }
11... Qa5 { Black breaks the pin on the f6-knight and threatens ...b7-b5. } 12.
Ra3
{ A standard response - now the rook is protected so that ...b7-b5 is prevented, and the rook might be useful elsewhere on the 3rd rank. }
12... Ne5 { Threatening ...Bxh3. } 13. Nf2 Nh5
{ Once again we find this move being played by strong GMs in the past few years. Let's explore the trend in our games and strive for active play against the Saemisch stronghold. }
14. Be2 f6
{ Before playing ...f5 Black first wants to push the g5-bishop to a less active square. }
15. Be3 f5 16. exf5 gxf5
{ White still can not castle:  17.O-O?  f4  wins a piece. } 17. Qc1 Ng6
{ A multipurpose move. The g7-bishop's diagonal as well as the e-file is opened, Black increases his control over the f4-square and the move is prophylaxis against f3-f4 by White. }
18. O-O Bd7 19. f4 Nf6
{ Black was doing very well in the correspondence game Pitkaenen, J.  2389  vs. Merrheim, X.  2289  , ICCF email 2012. He can occupy the e-file and think about moving a knight to e4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Fianchetto with Bf4"]
[Black "142. Fianchetto: 10. h3, 12. Bf4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. g3
{ The solid and popular Fianchetto System. White fortifies the kingside and attempts to create a position with no easy targets while planning to lay siege to the d6-square by placing a knight on c4  (with the e4-e5 break)  and/or playing Bf4. }
7... Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O Re8
{ I find this to be the most flexible move. Black controls the e4-square and reserves the option to play ...Ne4 or develop classically with ...Nbd7 and ...a7-a6. }
10. h3 { White plays a waiting game but Black can take active measures. } 10...
Bd7
{ A unique move that simply prepares queenside expansion with ...b7-b5. Of course if White plays a2-a4 then we will pounce on the b4-outpost with ...Na6. }
11. Qb3 Na6
{ Now if  12.Qxb7 ?  Black can play  12...Nb4  trapping the queen behind enemy lines. }
12. Bf4 b5
{ A great counter-attack when the d6-pawn is under fire. If White takes the bait then Black can follow with ...b5-b4 and ...Bb5. }
13. Nxb5 c4
{ An unexpected secondary pawn sacrifice to dislodge the queen and clear c5 for the knight.   If Black wants to play for more than a draw he could try  13...Bxb5  14.Qxb5  Nb4!?  followed by taking the d5-pawn at the right moment, but this continuation is not without risk. }
14. Qxc4 Rc8 15. Qb3 Nc5 16. Qc4 Na6
{ White's queen can't defend the b5-knight and at the same time escape the perpetual attack. }
*

