[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Fianchetto with Bf4"]
[Black "145. Fianchetto: Avrukh's 10. Bf4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. g3
{ The solid and popular Fianchetto System. White fortifies the kingside and attempts to create a position with no easy targets while planning to lay siege to the d6-square by placing a knight on c4  (with the e4-e5 break)  and/or playing Bf4. }
7... Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O Re8
{ I find this to be the most flexible move. Black controls the e4-square and reserves the option to play ...Ne4 or develop classically with ...Nbd7 and ...a7-a6. }
10. Bf4
{ Opening guru GM Boris Avrukh has suggested this in his most recent work and it is quickly becoming the mainline. }
10... h6
{ Black looks to play ...g6-g5 and bring White's entire opening plan into question. Also I will point out that   10...Bf5  is not mentioned by Avrukh and there have been many games now with short draws following  11.Nh4  Bc8  12.Nf3  etc. The system I am suggesting however leads to fighting chess in a still developing arena of Benoni theory. }
11. Qc1 { Avrukh's suggestion. White provokes a weakness on Black's kingside. }
11... g5 12. Bd2
{ This is older but has level results. White avoids the exchange sacrifice that happens after 12. Be3 but now his knight takes a longer route to the c4 square  (e1-c2-e3-c4)  which naturally allows Black to complete development. }
12... Bf5
{ If White does nothing now, Black will play ...Ne4 and after Nxe4 Bxe4 White can hardly avoid the exchange of light-squared bishops, which further eases Black's spatial problems. }
13. h4
{ This softens up Black's kingside a little, but White's pieces are not in a position to exploit those weaknesses. }
13... g4 14. Ne1 Kh7 { The h6-pawn was hanging. } 15. Nc2 Bg6
{ This secures both the g6-bishop and the f7-pawn in case White wants to open the f-file. }
16. Ne3 Qd7 { 16...Nbd7  17.Nc4  Ne5  is a valid alternative. } 17. Nc4 Na6
{ 17...b5?  18.Nxb5!  Qxb5  19.Nxd6  Qd7  20.Nxe8  Qxe8  21.Qxc5  ±   Now if  18.a4  we gain the b4-square,   while if  18.a3  Black can play  18...Nc7  and ...b7-b5. Black will have to react to  19.Bf4  with  Bf8.  It is a complicated game and needs further testing. }
*

