[Black "148. Fianchetto Traditional: 12. Nc4, 13. Nxe5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. g3
{ The solid and popular Fianchetto System. White fortifies the kingside and attempts to create a position with no easy targets while planning to lay siege to the d6-square by placing a knight on c4  (with the e4-e5 break)  and/or playing Bf4. }
7... Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O Re8
{ I find this to be the most flexible move. Black controls the e4-square and reserves the option to play ...Ne4 or develop classically with ...Nbd7 and ...a7-a6. }
10. Nd2
{ The traditional mainline. White prevents Black from playing ...Ne4 and is ready to expand with e2-e4 and Nc4. }
10... a6 11. a4 Nbd7 12. Nc4
{ This is premature here and allows Black to simplify the task. } 12... Ne5
{ 'Threatening' to exchange the strong c4-knight. } 13. Nxe5 Rxe5 14. Bf4 Re8
15. Qc2
{ White attempts to play 'simple' chess but Black has an easier time finding a plan. }
15... Rb8 { Intending ...b7-b5. } 16. a5 b5 17. axb6 Rxb6
{ Black is very active and ready to push White around with ...Nh5 perhaps followed by ...f7-f5. }
