[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Fianchetto Traditional"]
[Black "149. Fianchetto Traditional: 12. h3, 13. a5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. g3
{ The solid and popular Fianchetto System. White fortifies the kingside and attempts to create a position with no easy targets while planning to lay siege to the d6-square by placing a knight on c4  (with the e4-e5 break)  and/or playing Bf4. }
7... Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O Re8
{ I find this to be the most flexible move. Black controls the e4-square and reserves the option to play ...Ne4 or develop classically with ...Nbd7 and ...a7-a6. }
10. Nd2
{ The traditional mainline. White prevents Black from playing ...Ne4 and is ready to expand with e2-e4 and Nc4. }
10... a6 11. a4 Nbd7 12. h3
{ A smart move waiting for Black to declare the placement of d7-knight. White controls the g4-square so that in case of   12...Ne5  he can immediately kick the knight back with  13.f4  without having to worry about ...Ng4. }
12... Rb8 { Black's standard queenside expansion plan. } 13. a5
{ Deserves our attention. Black is now able to wage war against the c4 square with balanced play. }
13... b5 14. axb6 Nxb6
{ The knight is decently placed here, eyeing the d5-pawn and keeping White from placing his own knight on c4. }
15. Qc2 a5
{ Black has not scored so well from this position but I think the result will change with some tweaking. }
16. Rd1 Ba6 17. Nf1 Nc4 { Necessary because the a5-pawn was finally hanging. }
18. Rb1
{ We are following the game Avrukh - Nikolaidis 2003 when I here I like ...Ne5 and Black has a solid typical Benoni position.   18.b3  Nb6!  19.Rxa5?  Nbxd5  20.Rxa6  Nb4  ∓  and the b3-pawn makes an important difference, since White now can't play Qa4 saving some material. }
18... Ne5
{ This is my idea. I think we can provoke White into a pitched battle where all of Black's pieces will be on good squares.   The aforementioned Avrukh - Nikolaidis game continued  18...Qb6  19.b3  Ne5  20.Ne3  and Black's queen was somewhat misplaced, as otherwise he would have been able to equalize with 20... c4. }
19. f4 { The critical move, but at the same time very committal. } 19... Nc4
20. e4 Nd7 21. b3 Ncb6
{ It is not so easy for White to expand further without risk, while Black is ready to strike on the queenside with ...c4. }
*

