[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. g3
{ The solid and popular Fianchetto System. White fortifies the kingside and attempts to create a position with no easy targets while planning to lay siege to the d6-square by placing a knight on c4  (with the e4-e5 break)  and/or playing Bf4. }
7... Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O Re8
{ I find this to be the most flexible move. Black controls the e4-square and reserves the option to play ...Ne4 or develop classically with ...Nbd7 and ...a7-a6. }
10. Nd2
{ The traditional mainline. White prevents Black from playing ...Ne4 and is ready to expand with e2-e4 and Nc4. }
10... a6 11. a4 Nbd7 12. h3
{ A smart move waiting for Black to declare the placement of d7-knight. White controls the g4-square so that in case of   12...Ne5  he can immediately kick the knight back with  13.f4  without having to worry about ...Ng4. }
12... Rb8 { Black's standard queenside expansion plan. } 13. Nc4 Ne5 14. Na3
Nh5
{ Black flexes his wings on the kingside and prepares ...f7-f5 and an all out assault. }
15. e4 { Controlling the f5-square. } 15... Bd7
{ 15...f5  is also really interesting but 15... Bd7 has been firmly established as the best move. }
16. a5
{ White gives up the a-pawn to distract our queen and buy time for his pawn advances on the kingside. }
16... Qxa5
{ Armed with computer checked analysis we can confidently play this position and look to out-prepare and outplay the opposition. }
17. g4 Nf6 18. g5 Nh5 19. f4 Nc4
{ So far we are playing only moves. This move goads White into an exchange sacrifice where Black is equal or perhaps better. }
20. Nxc4 Qxa1 21. Nxd6 Bxc3
{ Black gives back the exchange in order to safely transition into a pleasant endgame. }
22. bxc3 Qxc3 23. Nxe8 Rxe8
{ White's doesn't have enough compensation for the pawn. Black is weak on the dark squares, but White has a lot of weaknesses himself. }
24. Rf2
{ Attempting to avoid the exchange of queens does not help anything, as White's pieces lack coordination against the three passed pawns. }
24... Ng3 25. e5 b5 { The pawns start running! } 26. Kh2 Nf5
{ This looked painful for White in D'Costa - Parligras, 2008. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Fianchetto Traditional"]
[Black "154. Fianchetto Traditional: 12. h3, 13. Nc4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. g3
{ The solid and popular Fianchetto System. White fortifies the kingside and attempts to create a position with no easy targets while planning to lay siege to the d6-square by placing a knight on c4  (with the e4-e5 break)  and/or playing Bf4. }
7... Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O Re8
{ I find this to be the most flexible move. Black controls the e4-square and reserves the option to play ...Ne4 or develop classically with ...Nbd7 and ...a7-a6. }
10. Nd2
{ The traditional mainline. White prevents Black from playing ...Ne4 and is ready to expand with e2-e4 and Nc4. }
10... a6 11. a4 Nbd7 12. h3
{ A smart move waiting for Black to declare the placement of d7-knight. White controls the g4-square so that in case of   12...Ne5  he can immediately kick the knight back with  13.f4  without having to worry about ...Ng4. }
12... Rb8 { Black's standard queenside expansion plan. } 13. Nc4 Ne5 14. Na3
Nh5
{ Black flexes his wings on the kingside and prepares ...f7-f5 and an all out assault. }
15. e4 { Controlling the f5-square. } 15... Bd7
{ 15...f5  is also really interesting but 15... Bd7 has been firmly established as the best move. }
16. a5
{ White gives up the a-pawn to distract our queen and buy time for his pawn advances on the kingside. }
16... Qxa5
{ Armed with computer checked analysis we can confidently play this position and look to out-prepare and outplay the opposition. }
17. g4 Nf6 18. g5 Nh5 19. f4 Nc4
{ So far we are playing only moves. This move goads White into an exchange sacrifice where Black is equal or perhaps better. }
20. Nxc4 Qxa1 21. Nxd6 Bxc3
{ Black gives back the exchange in order to safely transition into a pleasant endgame. }
22. bxc3 Qxc3 23. Rf3 { This allows us to force the exchange of queens. } 23...
Qd4+ 24. Qxd4 cxd4 25. Nxe8 Rxe8
{ Gata Kamsky played this complex endgame as Black against Fianchetto devotee Boris Avrukh in 2007 with success. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Fianchetto Traditional"]
[Black "155. Fianchetto Traditional: 12. h3, 13. Nc4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. g3
{ The solid and popular Fianchetto System. White fortifies the kingside and attempts to create a position with no easy targets while planning to lay siege to the d6-square by placing a knight on c4  (with the e4-e5 break)  and/or playing Bf4. }
7... Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O Re8
{ I find this to be the most flexible move. Black controls the e4-square and reserves the option to play ...Ne4 or develop classically with ...Nbd7 and ...a7-a6. }
10. Nd2
{ The traditional mainline. White prevents Black from playing ...Ne4 and is ready to expand with e2-e4 and Nc4. }
10... a6 11. a4 Nbd7 12. h3
{ A smart move waiting for Black to declare the placement of d7-knight. White controls the g4-square so that in case of   12...Ne5  he can immediately kick the knight back with  13.f4  without having to worry about ...Ng4. }
12... Rb8 { Black's standard queenside expansion plan. } 13. Nc4 Ne5 14. Na3
Nh5
{ Black flexes his wings on the kingside and prepares ...f7-f5 and an all out assault. }
15. e4 { Controlling the f5-square. } 15... Bd7
{ 15...f5  is also really interesting but 15... Bd7 has been firmly established as the best move. }
16. a5
{ White gives up the a-pawn to distract our queen and buy time for his pawn advances on the kingside. }
16... Qxa5
{ Armed with computer checked analysis we can confidently play this position and look to out-prepare and outplay the opposition. }
17. g4 Nf6 18. f4
{ This forces us to sacrifice a piece, since here  18...Nc4 ?  19.Nxc4  Qxa1  20.e5 !  is not a good idea for Black. }
18... Nexg4
{ In more than one example we see Black able to sacrifice the knight for two or three pawns with plenty of attacking chances. }
19. hxg4 Nxg4
{ If White does nothing now we can play ...Bd4+ and ...Qd8! intending ...Qh4+. }
20. f5
{ An idea we saw plenty of back in the Taimanov chapter. Here it does not really seem like White is playing for mate as much as trying to buy time for the defense. }
20... Ne5 { The knight was hanging. } 21. f6 Bh8
{ The bishop looks terrible here, but what about that beautiful e5-knight? Eventually Black's bishop will break out of its prison. }
22. Bg5 Qd8
{ The queen moves out of the a1-rook's stare and takes aim at the f6-pawn - at some point Black might play ...h6 to exchange his h-pawn for the f6-pawn. }
23. Nc2 b5 { A typical Benoni pawn sacrifice. } 24. Rxa6 b4 25. Ne2 Bb5
{ Black's pieces are all actively placed. He is ready to play ...h6. An alternative plan is ...Nd3 followed by ...Re5!? }
*

