[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Odds and Ends"]
[Black "157. Odds and Ends: 3. e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. e3
{ A quiet approach like this can't be critical. White is just trying to reach a playable position. }
3... g6
{ We will fianchetto and castle before deciding how to engage in the center. }
4. Nc3 Bg7 5. Nf3
{ Naturally this position can be reached from a number of move orders. } 5...
O-O 6. Be2 cxd4 7. exd4 d5
{ It has long been known that the fianchetto formation is one of the best ways to play against an isolated queen pawn. This position could be called the reverse Tarrasch. }
8. O-O Nc6 9. h3 dxc4 10. Bxc4 Na5 11. Be2 Be6
{ White does not have any attack and has a slightly worse pawn structure. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Odds and Ends"]
[Black "158. Odds and Ends: 3. e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. e3
{ A quiet approach like this can't be critical. White is just trying to reach a playable position. }
3... g6
{ We will fianchetto and castle before deciding how to engage in the center. }
4. Nc3 Bg7 5. Nf3
{ Naturally this position can be reached from a number of move orders. } 5...
O-O 6. Be2 cxd4 7. exd4 d5
{ It has long been known that the fianchetto formation is one of the best ways to play against an isolated queen pawn. This position could be called the reverse Tarrasch. }
8. c5
{ This is a popular approach in the regular Tarrasch with colors reversed. }
8... Nc6
{ Our counter is to put pressure on the d4-pawn with our minor pieces and then chip away at the c5-pawn with ...b7-b6 before White can reinforce it with b2-b4. }
9. O-O Ne4
{ Black boldly stakes claim to the center of the board and targets the d4-pawn. }
10. Be3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 b6
{ A key move in such structures for the battle of mobility. } 12. cxb6 axb6 13.
Qd2 Ba6
{ Exchanging off White's good bishop gives Black a more pleasant middlegame. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Odds and Ends"]
[Black "159. Odds and Ends: 3. dxc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. dxc5
{ Taking on c5 means that White gives up a central pawn for a flank pawn. All the same we need to make sure we regain the pawn. }
3... Na6
{ Black can also play  3...e6   or  3...Qa5+.  All are good but lead to different types of structures. The value of 3. .. Na6 is that Black can leave White guessing about how he will further develop. }
4. Be3
{ White takes up the challenge and forces Black to work to get the pawn back. }
4... e6
{ One of the few cases in this course that we won't be fianchettoing our bishop! }
5. a3 Bxc5 6. Bxc5 Nxc5 7. b4 Nce4 8. f3
{ Otherwise Black can just continue ...a7-a5 with a pleasant position. Now it looks as if our knight is trapped after   8...Ng5 ?  9.h4. }
8... Ng4 { Planning ...Qf6 looks quite fun to play. } 9. Qd4
{ Covering the a1-h8 diagonal and threatening Qxg7. } 9... Qg5 10. e3 Qh4+
{ An alternative try is  10...Nxe3  11.Qxe4  f5  12.Qd3   12.Qe5  Nc2+  Nxg2+  13.Kf2  Nf4  with an unclear position. }
11. g3 Nxg3 12. Qxg4 { White forces off the queens. } 12... Qxg4 13. fxg4 Nxh1
14. Bg2 g5
{ Planning ...h7-h5. This endgame remains untested in practical play. White has a slight material edge but Black's rooks can potentially become very active. }
*

