[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Odds and Ends"]
[Black "161. Odds and Ends: 4. dxe6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. dxe6
{ This is probably one of the worst ways that White can give up the center. Compare the Blumenfeld Gambit:  4.Nf3  b5!?  5.dxe6  fxe6  6.cxb5  , where White at least gets a pawn for his troubles! }
4... fxe6
{ Of course we should take back towards the center, increasing our control there. We will play ...d7-d5 and have a very nice center and easy development. }
5. Nc3 d5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Odds and Ends"]
[Black "162. Odds and Ends: 5. Nxd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. Nxd5
{ For some reason this move is even worse than it looks, even though it looks natural to try to maintain a piece on the d5-square. I guess we should listen to the rule about not bringing out the queen early. }
5... Nxd5 6. Qxd5 Nc6
{ We will just play calm developing moves and then chase away the queen with ...Be6. }
7. Nf3 Be7 8. e4 O-O 9. Be2 d6 10. O-O Be6 11. Qd2 Bf6
{ True, Black has a backward d-pawn, but in return has a punishing grip on the d4-square. }
12. Rd1 Re8
{ Of course  12...Nd4  is also strong, but I wanted to remind the reader of a little tactic. }
13. Qxd6 Nd4 14. Qxd8 Nxe2+ 15. Kf1 Bxd8 16. Kxe2 Bxc4+
{ This would leave White in a terrible spot. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Odds and Ends"]
[Black "163. Ods and Ends: 5. Nxd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. Nxd5
{ For some reason this move is even worse than it looks, even though it looks natural to try to maintain a piece on the d5-square. I guess we should listen to the rule about not bringing out the queen early. }
5... Nxd5 6. Qxd5 Nc6
{ We will just play calm developing moves and then chase away the queen with ...Be6. }
7. Nf3 Be7 8. Bg5 O-O
{ Here too we can just calmly develop and then play ...d6 and ...Be6. } 9. Bxe7
Qxe7 10. a3 d6 11. e3 Be6 12. Qd2 Rad8
{ If White refrains from putting a pawn on e4 we can solve the problem of our backward d6-pawn with ...d6-d5. }
13. Qc3 d5 14. cxd5 Bxd5
{ Followed by doubling rooks looks very pleasant for Black. } *

