[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. Training Positions"]
[Black "#7. The Battle for f4/e5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1r2nrk1/pp1b1p1p/3p2p1/2pPq3/P3P3/2N4P/1P1QBPP1/R3R1K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White is planning to play f2-f4 when the response ...Qd4+, exchanging queens, would give a slight edge to White in the endgame. How can Black maintain the dark square blockade ? }
1... Nf6
{ Now  19.f4  would lose a pawn due to  19...Qd4+  20.Qxd4  cxd4  and the guard of e4 is removed. }
2. Rad1 { Resuming the threat of f2-f4. } 2... g5
{ A key move for Black in many positions which allows him to maintain control over the dark squares. I will give two sample lines of thematic play.   19...Nxe4 ?  20.Nxe4  Qxe4  21.Bb5  Qf5  22.g4  and Black loses the d7-bishop. }
3. Rf1
{ 20.h4  h6  21.hxg5  hxg5  22.g3  Kh8 !  A rook on g8 plays well with a pawn on g5.  23.Kg2  Rg8  24.Rh1+  Kg7  25.f4  gxf4  26.gxf4  Kf8+  27.Kf1  Qe7  A typical Benoni situation: with White's overextended pawns there will be counter play against White's king. }
3... Nxe4 4. Nxe4 Qxe4 5. Qxg5+ Qg6 6. Qh4 Kh8 7. Rd3 f5 8. Rg3 Qf6
{ The game is balanced. } *

