[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Model Games"]
[Black "Game #1: Ilmars Graudins (2401) vs. Werner Schoen (2485), ICCF email 2012"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4 Bg7 8. Bb5+
Nfd7 9. a4 O-O 10. Nf3 Na6 11. O-O Nb4 12. Re1 a6 13. Bf1 Re8 14. h3 f5 15. Bd2
fxe4 16. Nxe4 Nf6 17. Nxf6+ Bxf6 18. Qb3 Rxe1 19. Rxe1 Bf5 20. g4 Bd7 21. Bc3
b5
{ The opening moves until here were discussed in line 8.   If you do not like the idea of sacrificing a pawn,  21...a5  has also been tried. }
22. a5 Rc8 { To occupy the c-file should White immediately take on b4 next. }
23. Kg2
{ 23.Bxb4  cxb4  24.Qxb4  Qc7!  and Black has good control over the dark squares to compensate for his pawn. }
23... Qf8 { Preparing ...Re8 to contest the e-file. } 24. Bxb4 cxb4 25. Bd3 Re8
26. Qxb4 Rxe1 27. Nxe1 Qe7
{ White has won a pawn but it is hard for him to make progress because Black is constantly threatening to invade on the dark squares, while White's bishop in particular has no clear targets. White also has several pawn weaknesses. }
28. Nc2 Be8 29. Kf3
{ White might want to offer the exchange of queens with Qe4. } 29... Bg7 30.
Ne3 h6 { Otherwise 31. g5 might be annoying. } 31. Be4 Qh4
{ It was also fine to sit tight with  31...Bf7. } 32. Qxd6
{ 32.Kg2  Qf6  33.Kf3  Qh4  is a possible repetition of moves. } 32... Qxh3+
33. Ke2 Bd4
{ The knight holds White's position together, so it is necessary to put pressure on it. }
34. Bf3 Qh2+ 35. Kd3 Qxb2 36. Nd1 Qa1 37. Qxa6 Bc5 38. Qe6+ Kf8 39. Qe5 Qb1+
{ Draw agreed. A perpetual is likely. We have seen that in this ending White can only make progress by opening up the position or moving his king away from the kingside, but both of these increase Black's counterplay over the dark squares. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Model Games"]
[Black "Game #2: Loek van Wely (2604) vs. Mahel Boyer (2295), Purtichju Open 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4 Bg7 8. Bb5+
Nfd7 9. Bd3 O-O 10. Nf3 Qa5
{ This is the new idea I recommended against 9. Bd3 in the Taimanov variation. }
11. Bd2 Na6 { Our theory section continues with  11...Re8  - see line 16. } 12.
a3 Re8 13. Rb1
{ It is clear that White has designs on the queenside, but why not castle first? }
13... Nf6 14. O-O c4
{ This advance was made possible because White waited so long with castling. }
15. Bc2 b5 16. Kh1 { 16.e5!?  was perhaps stronger. } 16... Qb6
{ Since it was no longer possible for Black to respond with ...Qb6 with check to a discovered attack on his queen  (after the c3-knight moves away)  , it had finally become necessary to move out of the e1-a5 diagonal. }
17. Qe1
{ Here too  17.e5   or  17.f5  would have given White good attacking chances, but Van Wely first wants to take control over the g1-a7 diagonal. }
17... Nc5
{ It was better to play on the c2-bishop's loose position with  17...b4!  18.Be3  Qb7  19.axb4  Nxb4  ∞  when White has some problems keeping the e4-pawn protected. }
18. Be3 Bb7 19. Rd1 a6
{ Again  19...b4  was called for. Slow play in the Benoni is often punished! }
20. e5 dxe5 21. fxe5 Ng4 22. Bd4
{ Here van Wely missed the clever move  22.Bg1!  , the point being that after  22...Nxe5  23.Nxe5  Rxe5  White has  24.Qf2!  with a double attack on f7 and the c5-knight. }
22... Nxe5 23. Nxe5 Bxe5 24. Bxe5 Nd7
{ Thanks to the pin Black regains his piece with an extra pawn to boot. } 25.
Qh4 Rxe5 { The knight remains on d7 to guard the important f6-square. } 26. Ne4
{ Van Wely still plays for a direct attack, but objectively this should not work. }
26... Bxd5 27. Ng5 Nf8
{ 27...Nf6!  -+ was much stronger, though Black does have to see that White's attack comes to nothing after  28.Rxf6  Qxf6  29.Qxh7+  Kf8. }
28. Qf4
{ The computer immediately finds the idea  28.Be4!  Bxe4  29.Nxe4  when White has some play on the weakened dark squares. }
28... f6 29. Nf3 Bxf3 { Simplifying the position. } 30. Qxf3 Rae8 31. b3 cxb3
32. Bxb3+ Kg7 33. Rc1 Rf5
{ Black is two pawns up for nothing so he does best to exchange pieces. } 34.
Qc3 Rxf1+ 35. Rxf1 Nd7 36. h3 Ne5 37. Rc1 Rd8 38. Qb4 Qd6 39. Qa5
{ Of course White wants to keep queens on the board to keep some vague attacking chances. }
39... Rd7 40. Rc8 Nd3 41. Qd2 Qf4
{ Now White can hardly avoid the exchange of queens. } 42. Qxf4 Nxf4
{ And although van Wely tried long and hard, he could not keep his much lower rated opponent from winning this endgame! }
43. a4 Rd3 44. Rc7+ Kh6 45. Bg8 bxa4 46. Rxh7+ Kg5 47. Ra7 Kh4 48. Kh2 Rd2 49.
Rh7+ Kg5 50. Kg3 Rxg2+ 51. Kf3 Rc2 52. h4+ Kf5 53. Ra7 Rc3+ 54. Kf2 Nd3+ 55.
Ke3 Nb4+ 56. Kd4 Nc6+ 57. Kxc3 Nxa7 58. Bh7 Nb5+ 59. Kb4 a3 60. Kb3 Kg4 61.
Bxg6 Kxh4 62. Be4 Kg4 63. Bb7 Nc7 64. Kxa3 f5 65. Bc8 Kg5 66. Kb4 f4 67. Kc5 f3
68. Kb6 f2 69. Bh3 Kh4 70. Bf1 Kg3 71. Bc4 Kg2 72. Kxc7 a5 73. Kb6 a4 74. Kc5
a3 75. Kd4 a2 { White resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Model Games"]
[Black "Game #3: Baadur Jobava (2646) vs. Viktor Bologan (2666), Turin Olympiad 2006"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f4 O-O 6. Nf3 c5 7. d5 e6 8. Be2 exd5
9. cxd5 Re8 10. e5 dxe5 11. fxe5 Ng4 12. e6 fxe6
{ Until here the game is following our line 29. } 13. Bg5
{ A very interesting novelty by Jobava back in 2006. } 13... Nf6
{ The critical test is undoubtedly  13...Qb6!  - hitting b2 -  14.Qd2  c4!  ,  threatening to enter on f2 with deadly effect. White probably has to play  15.O-O-O  but this looks extremely risky for him. }
14. d6
{ Now White, by mixing up the move order  (first Bg5 and only then d6)  , has hoodwinked Black into voluntarily retreating his knight to f6, when it was surely more actively positioned on g4! }
14... h6 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. Nb5
{ White immediately tries to win material, when he also could have settled for  16.O-O  += with a good position. }
16... Bd7
{ 16...Na6  is not possible on account of  17.d7  winning the c8-bishop. } 17.
Nc7 Nc6 18. Nxa8 Rxa8
{ Black has decent compensation for the exchange - he already has an extra pawn and b2 is likely to fall as well. Still, the d6-pawn is a thorn in his position. }
19. O-O Nb4 20. Qd2 Bc6
{ Bologan has designs on the d6-pawn, but he should have settled for  20...Qxb2  21.Qxb2  Bxb2  22.Rae1  +=. }
21. Rae1 Bd5 { With the idea of simply rounding up the d6-pawn. } 22. b3 Qc3
23. Bc4 { White offers a pawn to break open Black's central blockade. } 23...
Bxc4
{ The following line shows what White was going for:  23...Bxf3  24.Qxc3  Bxc3  25.gxf3  Bxe1  26.Rxe1  ±  the e6-pawn will fall and Black will have a hard time dealing with the dangerous d6-pawn and White's strong bishop. }
24. bxc4 Qxc4 25. Ne5
{ White could also have gone for material gains with  25.Qe3  followed by Qxe6+, but Jobava is always alert to any attacking possibilities and has noticed that Black's king hardly has any defenders left. }
25... Qc2 26. Qf4 { This leads to a well-calculated finish. } 26... Rf8
{ 26...Qf5  27.Qc4! } 27. d7 Rxf4 28. d8=Q+ Rf8 29. Rxf8+ Bxf8 30. Rf1
{ And mate in a few moves. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Model Games"]
[Black "Game #4: Dragoljub Jacimovic (2422) vs. Alexandr Fier (2587), Skopje 2014"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4 Qe7
{ This is my alternative suggestion against the four pawns attack. } 8. Nf3 Bg4
9. Bb5+ Nbd7 10. O-O O-O-O 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Bg7 13. Bd2 Ne8 14. Rae1 Bd4+
15. Kh1 Nc7 16. a4 Kb8 17. Bxd7 Qxd7 18. e5 Rhf8
{ The previous moves were discussed in line 43. Black's last move was a useful prophylactic move - in many lines  (e5-e6, Ne4xd6 etc.)  the f7-pawn either needs protection or the f-file is opened up. }
19. Ne4 { This amounts to an exchange of the d-pawns. } 19... Nxd5 20. Nxd6
{ White has a strong knight on d6, but by itself the knight doesn't do much, and Black's pieces have their fair share of central presence  (the d4-bishop and d5-knight)  . }
20... Qc6 21. Bc3 Bxc3 22. bxc3 Ne7
{ Black is a bit cramped so he looks to exchange pieces. } 23. Qxc6
{ 23.Ne4  was probably a better try. } 23... Nxc6
{ White is still slightly better in this endgame because his knight has better outposts, but this isn't an ending that Black has to be afraid of. }
24. Ne4 b6 25. Nf6 h6 26. e6
{ An alternative way to make some progress was  26.f5!? } 26... fxe6 27. Rxe6
Kc7 { 27...Ne7!  would have prevented the following breakthrough. } 28. f5 gxf5
29. Rxf5
{ It turns out that in this position Black has some problems defending the h6-pawn. }
29... Kb7
{ 29...Rf7!  was key. The point is that after  30.Rh5   the discovered attack  30.Nd5+  Kd7  isn't dangerous  Black can force an exchange of rooks with  30...Re7  31.Rxe7+  Nxe7  32.Rxh6  and then activate his king with  32...Kd6! }
30. Rh5 Rh8 31. Ne4 Rd1+ 32. Kh2 Ra1 33. Nd6+
{ Stockfish immediately finds  33.g4!  Rxa4  35.g5!  with a winning position. }
33... Ka6 34. Ne4 Kb7 35. Nd6+ Ka6 36. Ne4
{ Presumably White agreed to a draw by repetition because of time trouble, since the winning plan of  36.g4!  was still available. }
