[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Model Games"]
[Black "Game #5: Adam Cichocki (2292) vs. Alexey Kislinsky (2505), Poland 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. c4 c5 4. d5 Bg7 5. Nc3 O-O 6. e4 d6 7. Be2 e6 8. O-O Re8
9. Qc2 exd5 10. cxd5 Na6 { Thus far our theory section. } 11. Bg5
{ This move doesn't really fit in with White's position. } 11... h6 12. Bh4 g5
{ Kislinsky decides to immediately punish White for his unorthodox development by taking the bishop pair. }
13. Bg3 Nh5 14. Nd2 Nxg3 15. hxg3
{ 15.fxg3!  would have potentially given White a strong attack down the f-file. }
15... Nc7 16. Rfe1 Rb8 { Black is slowly but surely preparing ...b7-b5. } 17.
a4 Na6
{ 17...a6  18.a5  b5  19.axb6  Rxb6  would have been fine too, but Kislinsky is flexible and immediately returns to the plan of putting a knight on  b4  as he sees that White has weakened this square. }
18. Nc4 Nb4 19. Qd2
{ White still has ideas of playing f2-f4 and e4-e5, but unfortunately he is missing his dark-squared bishop to support that push... }
19... a6 20. a5 Bd4 21. Bh5 Qf6 22. Ra3
{ This allows a trick.  22.Na4  would have allowed White to fight for an advantage. }
22... Nd3
{ The knight is immune because after  23.Qxd3  Qxf2+  the e1-rook is now unprotected. }
23. Re2 Ne5
{ In this way Black forces the exchange of White's important c4-knight. } 24.
Nxe5
{ 24.Nb6?  Bg4!  25.Bxg4  Nxg4  and White has no defense against ...Qg6-h5. }
24... Rxe5 25. g4
{ Forcibly preventing Black from ever playing ...f7-f5. The g4-Bh5 setup resembles what is sometimes seen in the mainline of the Catalan opening on the other side of the board  (White's bishop on a5, pawn on b4)  . However, in this position White has no good way to increase the pressure on the f7-pawn, which means his h5-bishop isn't doing much for the rest of the game. }
25... Qe7 26. Kh1 b5
{ With the kingside being blocked, Black had to play this move sooner or later to make any progress. }
27. axb6 Rxb6 28. g3 Bb7
{ The immediate  28...Bxc3  29.Rxc3  Rxe4  was also possible. } 29. Kh2
{ White moves his king off the h1-a8 diagonal, but doesn't deal with all of Black's threats. }
29... Bxc3 30. Rxc3 Bxd5
{ The computer indicates that  30...Rxe4!  was even stronger. } 31. f3 Rb4
{ Black is for all intents and purposes a piece up, given the h5-bishop's pitiful state. }
32. Rce3 Bc4 33. Re1 Bb5 34. f4 gxf4 35. gxf4 Rexe4
{ White resigned, apparently missing that  36.Rxe4  Rxe4  37.Bxf7+!  would have given him some drawing chances, although Black should still be winning. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Model Games"]
[Black "Game #6: Shakhriyar Mamedyarov (2765) vs. Fabiano Caruana (2819), Paris Rapid 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 d6 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 7. e4 Bg7 8. h3
O-O 9. Bd3 b5 { This is what I recommend we play against the Modern mainline. }
10. a3 { This does not prevent ...b4 and hands the initiative to Black. } 10...
b4 11. Ne2
{ 11.axb4  cxb4  would give Black the open c-file to work with as well as a nice square on c5 for his knights. }
11... Re8 12. Qc2
{ It is difficult to say how White should defend the e4-pawn. } 12... Ba6
{ Intending to exchange one of the e4-pawn's defenders. } 13. Nd2 Bxd3 14. Qxd3
Nbd7 15. O-O a5
{ Black has a dream Benoni position. He has been able to expand significantly on the queenside and White can't finish his development without dropping the e4-pawn. }
16. Ng3 h5
{ White added a defender to the e4-pawn, so Black immediately creates the threat of chasing that defender away. }
17. Re1 Nb6
{ Caruana plays it safe.   17...Ne5  18.Qe2  Rc8  19.f4?!  Ned7  20.Qf3  c4  -+  and Black already has a decisive initiative. This is one of the many examples in the Benoni that shows that if White plays f2-f4 but is unable to carry on with e4-e5 or f4-f5 quickly, the advance of the f-pawn is just a weakening of his position. }
18. Re2 Nfd7 19. Nf3 Ne5 20. Nxe5 Bxe5 21. Nf1 c4 22. Qd1 b3
{ Fixing the b2-pawn and White now also constantly has to reckon with ...c4-c3. }
23. Nd2 a4 24. Nf3 c3 { Creating a protected passed pawn. } 25. bxc3 Bxc3
{ The rest of the game is easy - just improve your pieces, exchange them where possible and the b3-pawn will decide the game. }
26. Bg5 Bf6 27. h4 Rc8 28. Qd3 Nc4 29. Rc1 Ne5 { Forcing some exchanges. } 30.
Nxe5 Rxc1+ 31. Bxc1 Bxe5 32. g3 Qc7 33. Be3 Rb8 34. f4 b2 35. Qb1 Qc4 36. Kf2
Bd4 37. Bxd4 Qxd4+ 38. Kg2 Rb3
{ White resigned because of the impending ...Qc3 followed by ...Qc1. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Model Games"]
[Black "Game #7: Sergey Karjakin (2727) vs. Vugar Gashimov (2717), Sochi Grand Prix 2008"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 d6 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. e4
O-O 9. Bd3 a6
{ If you do not like the forcing variations of the Modern Mainline, this is my alternative suggestion. }
10. a4 Re8 11. O-O Nbd7 12. Re1 Nh5
{ This is my main idea, initiating play on the dark squares. } 13. Bg5 Bf6 14.
Be3 Ne5 15. Be2 Nxf3+ 16. Bxf3 Ng7 17. Qd2 b6
{ In line 76 I considered  17...Bd7. } 18. Rab1 Be5 { Intending ...f7-f5. } 19.
Bg5 { Of course White shouldn't allow the f-pawn's advance without a fight. }
19... f6 20. Bf4
{ Neither side would mind the exchange of dark-squared bishops, but only on their own terms! Black does not want to take on f4 or allow White to take on e5 after having played ...f6-f5. White on the other hand doesn't want to take on e5 as long as Black can retake ...fxe5  (though he eventually sees himself forced to do so)  . }
20... Ra7
{ This is a typical idea of a setup with ...a6 and ...b6 - Black swings his rook over to the kingside this way. }
21. b4
{ White wants to open lines on the queenside as he has a space advantage there. }
21... Rf7 22. Bd1 Qc7 23. bxc5 bxc5 24. Bxe5 fxe5
{ This change of pawn structure, which is often what Black wants to happen in the 9... a6 variation, makes the game resemble a king's indian. White now primarily wants to play on the queenside via the b-file while Black wants to set up an attack on the f-file, utilizing the f4-square. However In this game White also creatively involves his queen in the attack via the kingside. }
25. Qg5
{ The computer suggests  25.Be2  Ref8  26.Nd1!?  Nh5  27.a5  Nf4  28.Bf1  when White is ready to enter the queenside with Rb6, but Black has some attacking chances with for example ...Qe7-g5. }
25... Ref8 26. Rb2 Rf4 27. Bg4 Qa5 28. Re3 Qc7 29. Re1 Qa5 30. Rc1 Bxg4 31.
hxg4 c4 32. Qh6 { Intending an attack with Rb7. } 32... Qc5
{ Counter-attacking against f2. } 33. Nd1 Qd4 34. Rb7 R4f7 35. Rcb1
{ After this move the game is likely to end in a repetition of moves - one pair of rooks will be exchanged, after which White can repeat with Rb8+ ...Rf8 Rb7 ...Rf7 etc.   If White wanted to play for a win  35.Rxf7  Rxf7  36.Qe3!?  += was possible. }
35... Rxb7 36. Rxb7 Qxd1+ 37. Kh2 Rf7 38. Rb8+ Rf8 39. Rb7 Rf7 40. Rb8+ Rf8 41.
Rb7 { Draw agreed. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Model Games"]
[Black "Game #8: Vladimir Antoshin (2470) vs. Lev Psakhis (2500), Sochi 1979"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bg5 Bg7 8. e3
h6 9. Bh4 g5 10. Bg3 Nh5 11. Bd3 O-O 12. Nd2 Nxg3 13. hxg3
{ We analyzed the opening until here in line 92. } 13... Nd7
{ This knight should be brought out before White can lock down the queenside with Nc4 and a2-a4. }
14. Nc4
{ Antoshin, V. vs. Gorelov, S., Moscow 1981 continued   14.Qc2  Qe7  15.Bf5  Qe8 ?!  16.Nc4  b5 ?  17.a4 ?!  It is hard to see what was wrong with   17.Nxb5.  b4  18.Nd1 ?!  Ba6  19.Bd3  b3 !?  20.Qb1 ?!  Bb7  21.Be4  Ne5  22.Qc1 ?  Bxd5 !  23.Bf5   23.Bxd5  Nd3+  Bxg2  24.Rg1  Bd5  -+  and Black soon won. }
14... Nb6
{ 14...Ne5 ?  15.Nxe5  and Black can't recapture with the bishop because the h6-pawn would be hanging. }
15. Nxb6
{ In case of   15.Nd2  Bd7  Black continues similarly with ...f7-f5 and ...Qf6. }
15... Qxb6 16. Qc2 { 16.Rb1  immediately was preferable. } 16... Bd7
{ Black simply finishes development after which he will start with an attack along the e- and f-files. }
17. Rb1 f5 18. g4
{ Stockfish suggests the interesting   18.Kf1  Rae8  19.Kg1  ,  but Black also keeps the initiative here. }
18... fxg4 { White's attack is a mirage - it is safe to capture this pawn. }
19. Bh7+ Kh8 20. Ne4 Qa5+ 21. Kf1 Qxa2 22. Nxd6
{ Or   22.Nxg5  g3 !  23.f3  Qxd5  with similar results. } 22... g3 23. f3 Qxd5
24. Rd1 Qe5
{ 24...Rxf3+ !  25.gxf3  Qxf3+  26.Kg1  Rf8 !  would have given Black a crushing attack. The threat is ...Qxe3+ Kg2 Rf2+. For example  27.Re1   27.Nc4  Bc6!  Qf2+  28.Qxf2  gxf2+  and wins. }
25. Be4 Be6 26. Nxb7 Rab8 27. b3 Bxb3
{ White resigned because of   28.Qxb3  Qxe4  with the double threat ...Rxb7 and ...Rxf3+. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Model Games"]
[Black "Game #9: Nigel Short (2655) vs. Johann Hjartarson (2547), Nuuk Rapid 2016"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Bd3 O-O 6. Nge2 c5 7. d5 e6 8. O-O
exd5 9. cxd5
{ Via a Kings Indian move order we have arrived into the Penrose variation of the Modern Benoni. }
9... a6 10. a4 Re8 11. Ng3 Nbd7 12. h3 Rb8
{ In the theory section I recommend   12...Qc7  but the text move is not bad either. }
13. f4 b5
{ A familiar trick, playing on the weakness of the e4-pawn.  Black can also try   13...c4 !?  14.Bxc4  b5 !  with similar play. }
14. axb5 c4 15. Bxc4
{ 15.Bc2  axb5  and Black has already made serious progress on the queenside. }
15... axb5 16. Bd3
{ After   16.Bxb5  Rxb5 !  17.Nxb5  Qb6+  18.Nd4  Nxe4  19.Nge2  Ba6  White will find it impossible to hold on to his extra material. A possible continuation is  20.Kh2  Bxd4  21.Rxa6 !  Qxa6  22.Nxd4  Qc4  and Black will soon win the d5-pawn, restoring material equality. }
16... b4 17. Na4 Qa5 { Pinning the knight and preparing ...Ba6. } 18. Bd2 Ba6
19. Qf3 Bxd3 20. Qxd3 h5
{ Taking over the initiative. Suddenly the e4-pawn is in danger. } 21. Rfe1 Ra8
{ 21...Qb5 !  ∓,  intending to exchange another defender of the e4-pawn, was stronger. The position is similar to the Benko Gambit, where despite being a pawn down Black would like to trade pieces so that he can exploit White's weak pawns better. }
22. Nf1 Qa6
{ Now the exchange of queens only leads to a slightly better ending for Black. }
23. Qxa6 Rxa6 24. Bxb4 Rea8 25. b3 { Necessary. } 25... Nxe4 26. Rad1 f5
{ Cementing the powerful e4-knight. } 27. Rd3 Rb8 28. Ba3 Ndc5
{ The computer prefers   28...Ndf6  29.Bb2  h4 !  ∓  when White can hardly make a move without losing material. }
29. Bxc5 dxc5 30. Ne3
{ This leads to new problems.   30.Nd2  would have been close to equal. } 30...
Bd4 31. Kf1 Rxb3
{ A nice tactic but it should lead to nothing special, whereas Black is close to winning after   31...Bxe3  32.Rdxe3  c4  33.Nc3  Nxc3  34.Rxc3  cxb3. }
32. Rxb3 Nd2+ 33. Ke2 Nxb3 34. Rb1 Rxa4 35. Rxb3 Bxe3 36. Rxe3
{ Now Black simply wins a pawn.   36.Kxe3 = } 36... Rxf4 37. d6 Kf7 38. Re7+
Kf6 39. Rc7 c4 40. d7 Ke7 41. g3
{ 41.Rc6  g5  42.Rd6 !  and the endgame would perhaps still be salvageable. }
41... Re4+ 42. Kf3 Kd8 43. Rc6 Kxd7 44. Rxg6 c3 45. Ra6 Rc4 46. Ra1 Ke6 47. Ke3
c2 48. Kd2 Ke5 49. Re1+ Re4 50. Rf1 h4 51. gxh4 Rxh4 52. Kxc2 Rxh3 53. Kd2 Ke4
54. Rg1 f4 55. Ke1 Kf3 56. Rf1+ Ke3 57. Rg1 f3 58. Kf1 Rh8 *

