[White "18. Model Games"]
[Black "Game #10: Sahaj Grover (2479) vs. Aleksandar Indjic (2549), Kocaeli 2013"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f3 a6 8. a4 Bg7
9. Nge2 Nbd7 10. Ng3 h5 11. Be2 Qe7 12. Be3
{ In the theory section we looked at  12.O-O  - line 126, but play remains the same. Black can advance his h-pawn and play on the dark squares. }
12... h4 13. Nf1 Ne5 14. h3
{ Note that  14.f4?  is not possible because after  14...Neg4  White has problems protecting the e4-pawn.  The text move prevents Black from ever playing ...h4-h3, but also creates a new weakness on g3. }
14... Rb8 15. Bg5 Rh5 16. Be3 g5 { Securing the position of the e5-knight. }
17. g4
{ This amounts to an unnecessary pawn sacrifice.  17.Qd2  was called for. }
17... hxg3 18. Nxg3 Rxh3 19. Rxh3 Bxh3 20. Qd2
{ White intends to castle long and make use of the open h-file, whereas Black can no longer castle. }
20... g4 21. Nf5 Qf8 22. fxg4
{ It was probably stronger to chase Black's e5-knight away with  22.f4. } 22...
Bxg4 23. Nxg7+ Qxg7 24. O-O-O
{ The situation looks dangerous for Black, but with his extra pawn and strong knight on e5 he should eventually come out on top. }
24... Bxe2 25. Qxe2 Qg4 { Attacking e4 and offering the exchange of queens. }
26. Qh2 Kd7
{ 26...Ke7  would allow  27.Bxc5!  Qg5+  28.Kb1  dxc5  29.Rg1  Nfg4  30.Rxg4!  ± }
27. Bf4
{ Now  27.Bxc5?  doesn't work because after  27...Qg5+  28.Kb1  dxc5  29.Rg1  Nfg4  30.Rxg4  Qxg4  -+  the capture on e5 doesn't come with check. }
27... Re8 28. Rf1
{ 28.Bxe5  was necessary, but that is not a move you play because you want to. }
28... Nd3+ 29. Kb1 Nxe4 30. Nxe4 Rxe4 31. Bg3 Qg6 32. Bh4 Ne5
{ Black has a decisive attack.  33.Ka2  is met by  33...Rxa4+  ,   While  33.Kc1  Rc4+  leads to mate. }
*

[Event "?"]
