[White "18. Model Games"]
[Black "Game #11: Koen Leenhouts (2483) vs. Jorden van Foreest (2640), Amsterdam 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f3 O-O 6. Bg5 c5 7. d5 e6 8. Qd2 exd5
9. cxd5 a6 10. a4 Qa5 11. Ra3 Nbd7 12. Nh3 Ne5 13. Nf2 Nh5 14. Be2 f5
{ In the theory section I recommend first kicking the g5-bishop back with   14...f6  before further advancing the f-pawn. See line 138 for the details. }
15. exf5 gxf5 16. O-O Ng6 17. Bh6
{ White intends to exchange dark-squared bishops and then put his pawns on the dark squares  (g3, f4)  , but this takes a lot of time and allows Black to take the initiative. }
17... Bd7 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. g3 Rae8 20. f4 Nf6
{ White chased the knight to f6, but it probably wanted to go there anyway since e4 is looking like a nice square. }
21. Bf3 Rf7 22. Raa1 Rfe7 23. Nce4
{ White would like to alleviate Black's activity with  23.Rfe1  and rook exchanges, but that would give Black the opportunity to play  23...b5!  Instead he settles for the exchange of queens, but that leads to the same thing. }
23... Qxd2 24. Nxd2 b5 25. axb5 Bxb5
{ The typical recapture  25...axb5  would give White some much needed counterplay with  26.Ra6.  The text compromises Black's pawn structure, but White is not in a position to make use of that, and it activates Black's bishop. }
26. Rfc1 Re3 27. Kg2 Re2
{ Very energetic play, but there was nothing wrong with  27...Ne7  28.Nc4  Bxc4  29.Rxc4  Nexd5  30.Bxd5  Nxd5  ∓ with a clear extra pawn, since  31.Rxa6?  Re2  - threatening ...Ne3+ -  32.Rc1  Rd2!  33.Kg1  Nf6!  followed by ...Ree2 leaves Black with a decisive attack. }
28. Nc4 { 28.Bxe2  Rxe2  29.Nc4  Ne4  and Black wins material. } 28... Bxc4 29.
Rxc4 Rxb2 30. Rxa6
{ 30.Rca4!  would have been a better defense, the point being that White can contest the 2nd rank after for example  30...Ng4   30...Ne7!?  ∓  31.Bxg4  fxg4  32.R4a2. }
30... Ng4 31. Bxg4 fxg4
{ Now it is almost impossible for White to defend the f2-knight. } 32. Kf1 Rb1+
33. Kg2 Re2 34. Re4 Rd2 35. f5 Rbb2 36. fxg6 Rxf2+ 37. Kg1 hxg6 38. Rxd6 Rg2+
39. Kf1 Rxh2 40. Kg1 Rhd2
{ Black is preparing ...Rd3 and ...Rbd2, but it was stronger to immediately start advancing his passed c-pawn. }
41. Re1 Rd3 42. Kh1 Kh6 43. Rd8 Rbd2 44. Rh8+ Kg7 45. Rh4 Rxg3
{ Black will force the exchange of a pair of rooks with ...Rh3+ after which the remaining endgame is easily won. }
