1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 Bg7 8. Nd2
O-O 9. Nc4 Nh5 10. Qd2
{ As we discussed in the section on the Knight's Tour variation,  10.Bxd6  is a more critical try here. }
10... Nxf4 11. Qxf4 Nd7 12. e3
{ In the theory section  12.Qxd6  was considered - see line 103. } 12... Ne5
{ Now Black has the bishop pair and easy development while White doesn't even have a pawn to show for it. }
13. Rc1 f5 14. h4
{ The point of Black's last move is that  14.Be2?  g5  traps the queen. } 14...
a6 { The immediate  14...b5  was possible too. } 15. Be2
{ 15.a4  b5!  16.axb5  axb5  17.Nxb5  Nxc4  18.Bxc4  Be5!  19.Qf3  f4  and Black already has a decisive initiative. }
15... b5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. Qg5 Bf6
{ Of course Black should not exchange queens. } 18. Qf4 Be5 19. Qg5 Bf6 20. Qf4
Ra7 { Nor should he agree to a draw by repetition of moves! } 21. g3 Re7 22.
Bf3
{ 22.Kf1  would have kept White in the game, though Black holds all the cards. }
22... Be5 23. Qg5 Kg7 { Threatening ...h6 trapping White's queen. } 24. e4 f4
25. h5 Bf6 { Or  25...Bxc3+  26.Rxc3  Rxe4+!  27.Bxe4  Qxg5. } 26. h6+
{ 26.Qxf4  Bxc3+  27.Rxc3  Rxf4. } 26... Kg8 { Her majesty is caught. } *

