1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 d6 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 7. Bf4 Bg7 8. Qa4+
Bd7 9. Qb3 b5 10. Bxd6 Qb6 11. Be5 O-O 12. e3 b4 13. Nb1 a5
{ In the theory section we continue  13...Bf5  - see line 110. } 14. a4
{ White should not allow ...a4. } 14... Bg4 15. Nbd2 Nbd7 16. Bb5 Rfd8 17. Bg3
{ Perhaps a better try is  17.Nc4!?  Qa7  18.Bxf6  Bxf6  19.Nfd2  when White can follow up with f2-f3 and e3-e4. }
17... Bxf3 18. gxf3
{ 18.Nxf3  would allow  18...Ne4   or even  18...c4!?  19.Qxc4  Rac8  with a lot of activity for Black. }
18... Qa7 { Making space for ...Nb6. } 19. O-O
{ 19.e4  ,  reinforcing the d5-pawn, was the critical move. } 19... Nxd5 20.
Bc6 { This is what White was counting on, but he is in for a surprise. } 20...
c4 21. Nxc4 { 21.Qxc4  N7b6  followed by ...Rac8 and Black is very active. }
21... Nc5 22. Qc2 Rac8 23. Bxd5 Rxd5 24. Nd6
{ White still has some advantage, but it is considerably more difficult to make this extra f-pawn count than was the case when his extra pawn was a passed pawn on the d-file. }
24... Rc6 25. Rad1 Rxd1 { 25...Rh5!? } 26. Rxd1 Qa6 27. Nb5 Ne6 28. Qb3 h5 29.
h4 Bf6 30. Rd6
{ Gelfand wants to exchange more pieces before trying to make use of his extra pawn, but perhaps  30.e4!?  Rc5  31.f4  was a better try. }
30... Rxd6 31. Nxd6 Qc6 32. Qc4 { Giving up the extra pawn.   32.Kg2  += }
32... Qxf3 33. Qc8+ Nf8 34. Qc2 Be7 35. Nc4 Qd5 36. b3 Ne6 37. Qd2 Qxd2 38.
Nxd2
{ Black now has a small advantage on account of his superior pawn structure, but it doesn't amount to much. His main problem is that the a5-pawn is fixed on a dark square, same as the bishops, and thus needs constant supervision. }
38... Bd8 39. Kf1 Nc5 40. Ke2 f5 41. Bd6 Nb7 42. Bg3 Kf7 43. e4 fxe4 44. Nxe4
Ke6 45. Kd3 Kd5 46. f3 Be7 47. Bf2 Nd8 48. Bb6 Nc6
{ A better try seems  48...Kc6!  49.Bf2   49.Bxa5?  Nb7  and the bishop is trapped  Ne6  50.Nd2  g5  ∓ and Black has created an outside passed pawn. }
49. Bf2 Ne5+ 50. Ke2 Bd8 51. Nd2 Nc6 52. Kd3 Ne5+ 53. Ke2 Nc6 54. Kd3 *

