1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 c5 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Bg2 Bg7 8. Nf3
O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. Bf4 { This is the line that GM Boris Avrukh popularized. }
10... h6 11. Qc1 g5 12. Bd2 Bf5 13. h4 g4 14. Ne1 Kh7
{ For comments until here, see the theory section - line 145. } 15. a4
{ White should prefer the immediate manoeuvre  15.Nc2  Ne3-c4. It wasn't yet necessary to constrain the queenside with a2-a4. }
15... Na6
{ With the bishop already on f5, the knight hop to b4 gains in strength. } 16.
Nc2 Bg6
{ A prophylactic move, securing both the bishop and the f7-pawn, though  16...Nb4!?  was also strong. }
17. Bf4 Nh5 18. Be3 { The bishop is very unfortunately placed here. } 18... Nb4
19. Na3
{ After  19.Nxb4  cxb4  20.Nd1  Rc8  21.Qd2  a5  Black has a strong initiative. Even so this was better than 19. Na3, which simply loses. }
19... Nxg3 20. fxg3 Rxe3
{ Winning material because of  21.Qxe3?  Bd4.  this line also shows the value of the prophylactic move 16... Bg6, since the f-file is quite often opened up. }
21. Kh2 Re8
{ Timman missed the beautiful rook sacrifice  21...Be5!!  22.Qxe3  Qxh4+  23.Kg1  Bxg3  with a decisive attack. }
22. Qf4 h5 23. Ne4 Kg8 24. Ng5
{ White plays for an attack, but this simply doesn't work. } 24... Rxe2 25. Nc4
Nxd5 26. Qxd6 Rxg2+ { A nice combination to finish the game with. } 27. Kxg2
Ne3+ *

