1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 c5 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Bg2 Bg7 8. Nf3
O-O 9. O-O a6 10. a4 Re8 11. Nd2
{ This is the main line of the fianchetto variation. } 11... Nbd7 12. h3 Rb8
13. Nc4 Ne5 14. Na3 Nh5 15. e4 Bd7 16. a5 Qxa5 17. g4 Nf6 18. f4 Nexg4 19. hxg4
Nxg4 20. f5 h5
{ In the theory section we continued  20...Ne5  - see line 155. } 21. Bg5 Qb4
22. f6 Bh8 23. Qd2 Qd4+ 24. Qxd4 cxd4
{ Stockfish gives White some advantage in this endgame, but in practice it is very hard to play for White with his pawn weaknesses  (b2, e4, f6)  and loose pieces. }
25. Ne2 Re5 26. Bh4
{ After  26.Bf4  the exchange sacrifice  26...Bxf6!?  27.Bxe5  Bxe5  ∞ looks very interesting. White has a rook  (!)  for four pawns, but Black has control over the dark squares and a couple of dangerous passed pawns. Still this was clearly preferable to 26. Bh4. }
26... Ne3 { Threatening both 27... Nxf1 and 27... Nxg2 28. Kxg2 Rxe4. } 27.
Nxd4 Nxg2
{ The e4-pawn is more important than the exchange. After  27...Nxf1?!  28.Rxf1  += White would have retained control over the position. }
28. Kxg2 Rxe4 29. Nf3 Bf5 30. Rac1 Rbe8
{ 30...Rg4+  31.Kf2  Be4!  would have won at least another pawn. } 31. Nc4 Rg4+
32. Kf2 Bd3 { Now  32...Be4  33.Nxd6  would be in White's favor. } 33. Ne3
{ It was easy to miss the move  33.Rfe1!!  , giving up more material. The point is that after  33...Rxe1  34.Rxe1  Bxc4  35.Re8+  Kh7  36.Ng5+  Rxg5  37.Bxg5  Bxd5  Black has four pawns for the exchange, but his king, dark-squared bishop and kingside pawns are completely paralyzed, and White can mop up the a-, b- and d-pawns with his rook. Note that an attempt to break out with ...h4 should not be met by Bxh4? but by Kg1-h2-h3, keeping Black's king locked up. }
33... Bxf1 34. Nxg4 hxg4 35. Kxf1 gxf3
{ Now Black should be easily winning as his king and h8-bishop can easily break out of their confinement. }
36. Rc7 Re5 37. Rc8+ Kh7 38. Rf8 g5 39. Rxf7+ Kg6 40. Rf8 Bxf6 41. Bg3 *

